95
00:04:35,400 --> 00:04:42,240
So if you remember,
we basically studied

96
00:04:42,240 --> 00:04:44,160
a new kind of
architecture, which

97
00:04:44,160 --> 00:04:48,160
was called the mixture
of experts, which is such

98
00:04:48,160 --> 00:04:50,840
that if you have an
input, what you want

99
00:04:50,840 --> 00:04:54,900
is to not necessarily
activate all the parameters.

100
00:04:54,900 --> 00:04:59,820
And so you are in a setting
where you have multiple experts,

101
00:04:59,820 --> 00:05:02,800
and in the forward pass, you
only activate some of them.

102
00:05:02,800 --> 00:05:04,580
So that's a sparse MOE.

103
00:05:04,580 --> 00:05:06,500
You also have the
dense MOE, which

104
00:05:06,500 --> 00:05:09,620
basically weights the
outputs as a function

105
00:05:09,620 --> 00:05:13,300
of the output of the gate.

106
00:05:13,300 --> 00:05:17,780
So we saw that this
architecture was used in LLMs,

107
00:05:17,780 --> 00:05:20,700
and it was mainly used
to be able to scale

108
00:05:20,700 --> 00:05:24,592
this LLMs without
incurring an expensive cost

109
00:05:24,592 --> 00:05:26,300
at inference time,
because you don't want

110
00:05:26,300 --> 00:05:29,820
to activate all the parameters.

111
00:05:29,820 --> 00:05:32,780
The second thing
that we saw was just

112
00:05:32,780 --> 00:05:36,260
defining what an LLM
was and in particular,

113
00:05:36,260 --> 00:05:41,740
how you could decide on what
the next token prediction is.

114
00:05:41,740 --> 00:05:44,540
So we saw three methods.

115
00:05:44,540 --> 00:05:48,060
First one was we
called greedy decoding,

116
00:05:48,060 --> 00:05:52,320
which was always taking
the highest probable token.

117
00:05:52,320 --> 00:05:55,280
The second method we
saw was beam search,

118
00:05:55,280 --> 00:06:00,640
where we kept track of the
K most probable sequences.

119
00:06:00,640 --> 00:06:04,560
And then the third
one was sampling.

120
00:06:04,560 --> 00:06:07,260
So we're not doing
the most probable.

121
00:06:07,260 --> 00:06:10,080
We're not keeping track of the
highest probable sequences.

122
00:06:10,080 --> 00:06:13,880
What we do is we sample
the next token with respect

123
00:06:13,880 --> 00:06:16,640
to the distribution
that we get as outputs.

124
00:06:16,640 --> 00:06:19,000
And then we saw there's
this hyperparameter that's

125
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:20,640
called temperature
that allows you

126
00:06:20,640 --> 00:06:28,000
to tweak how spiky you want your
distribution to like versus not.

127
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:34,520
And we also saw some inference
optimization techniques,

128
00:06:34,520 --> 00:06:38,720
which are used in
practice to avoid having

129
00:06:38,720 --> 00:06:41,640
a big cost at decoding time.

130
00:06:41,640 --> 00:06:44,320
So I'm not going to
just mention everything,

131
00:06:44,320 --> 00:06:46,060
but I would say KV
cache, for instance,

132
00:06:46,060 --> 00:06:48,040
is an important method.

133
00:06:48,040 --> 00:06:50,900
So yeah, just
recommend just knowing

134
00:06:50,900 --> 00:06:54,140
what it is along
with the other ones.

135
00:06:54,140 --> 00:06:59,020
And with that, we're
going to start lecture 4.

136
00:06:59,020 --> 00:07:01,820
And actually, I was really
looking forward to today

137
00:07:01,820 --> 00:07:05,580
because lecture 1, we
saw what self-attention

138
00:07:05,580 --> 00:07:07,740
was, what a transformer was.

139
00:07:07,740 --> 00:07:11,300
Second lecture, we
saw some of the tricks

140
00:07:11,300 --> 00:07:14,100
that people use today and
some of the variations

141
00:07:14,100 --> 00:07:15,460
from the transformer.

142
00:07:15,460 --> 00:07:19,100
We introduced what an
LLM was last lecture.

143
00:07:19,100 --> 00:07:21,620
And this lecture,
we're finally going

144
00:07:21,620 --> 00:07:25,180
to see how these
LLMs are trained.

145
00:07:25,180 --> 00:07:28,310
So today, we're going to
focus on LLM training.

146
00:07:31,180 --> 00:07:32,900
And the first thing
that I'm going to say

147
00:07:32,900 --> 00:07:38,060
is if you've been
in the ML field for,

148
00:07:38,060 --> 00:07:42,300
let's say, more than
a few years now, you

149
00:07:42,300 --> 00:07:46,200
may have noticed
that traditionally,

150
00:07:46,200 --> 00:07:49,400
if you had a task,
what you would do

151
00:07:49,400 --> 00:07:53,920
is train a model
specifically for that task.

152
00:07:53,920 --> 00:07:56,600
So let's suppose 10
years ago, let's suppose

153
00:07:56,600 --> 00:08:01,040
we had a task which was
around detecting spam.

154
00:08:01,040 --> 00:08:04,880
You would train a model
specifically to detect spams.

155
00:08:04,880 --> 00:08:06,720
So you would train
on the training set,

156
00:08:06,720 --> 00:08:10,280
eval on the validation set,
and then test on the test set.

157
00:08:10,280 --> 00:08:13,680
If you had another use case,
let's suppose sentiment

158
00:08:13,680 --> 00:08:18,440
extraction, you would train
a model specifically for that

159
00:08:18,440 --> 00:08:21,280
and so on and so forth.

160
00:08:21,280 --> 00:08:26,440
But one could argue
that these tasks,

161
00:08:26,440 --> 00:08:29,280
they are not
completely disjoint.

162
00:08:29,280 --> 00:08:35,159
They're all involving just
understanding the text.

163
00:08:35,159 --> 00:08:39,919
So one could argue
we could find a way

164
00:08:39,919 --> 00:08:43,500
to somehow leverage the
knowledge that we acquired

165
00:08:43,500 --> 00:08:46,620
during training for,
let's say, one task

166
00:08:46,620 --> 00:08:50,340
and reuse that for another task.

167
00:08:50,340 --> 00:08:52,000
So this method has a name.

168
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:53,860
It's been around for
some time, and it's

169
00:08:53,860 --> 00:08:56,580
called transfer learning.

170
00:08:56,580 --> 00:08:58,860
So the goal of
transfer learning is

171
00:08:58,860 --> 00:09:02,420
to not always start from
scratch if you have a new task.

172
00:09:02,420 --> 00:09:06,560
It's to start with
some pre-trained model,

173
00:09:06,560 --> 00:09:09,740
and we're going to see what
pre-trained is, and then

174
00:09:09,740 --> 00:09:16,780
tune it for your task instead
of starting from scratch.

175
00:09:16,780 --> 00:09:19,540
Well, it's basically
the paradigm

176
00:09:19,540 --> 00:09:21,940
on which LLMs are trained.

177
00:09:21,940 --> 00:09:26,900
So the idea here is
that all these tasks,

178
00:09:26,900 --> 00:09:30,220
they involve
understanding language.

179
00:09:30,220 --> 00:09:35,500
So what we're going to do is
have what we call a pre-training

180
00:09:35,500 --> 00:09:41,880
stage, which involves training
your LLM on vast amounts of data

181
00:09:41,880 --> 00:09:44,220
to just understand
what language,

182
00:09:44,220 --> 00:09:50,920
what code is and then have a
second stage of, quote unquote,

183
00:09:50,920 --> 00:09:52,400
"tuning."

184
00:09:52,400 --> 00:09:55,560
And we're going to see a
little bit what that tuning is.

185
00:09:55,560 --> 00:09:58,040
But in that second
stage, we're going

186
00:09:58,040 --> 00:10:02,920
to take our pre-trained model
and somehow find a way to tune

187
00:10:02,920 --> 00:10:08,000
the weights to adapt
to a specific task.

188
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:12,420
So as an example, here, we
would pre-train a huge model

189
00:10:12,420 --> 00:10:14,520
and then suppose
for spam detection.

190
00:10:14,520 --> 00:10:18,640
We would somehow tune it for
that sentiment extraction, same.

191
00:10:18,640 --> 00:10:22,200
We would tune it
for that and so on.

192
00:10:22,200 --> 00:10:25,160
So this is just to take
the example from before.

193
00:10:25,160 --> 00:10:29,487
And the idea here is in
order to obtain these models,

194
00:10:29,487 --> 00:10:31,070
we're not going to
start from scratch.

195
00:10:34,800 --> 00:10:36,560
Cool.

196
00:10:36,560 --> 00:10:39,200
So now, we're going to
see what pre-training is.

197
00:10:39,200 --> 00:10:42,460
So pre-training
is by far the most

198
00:10:42,460 --> 00:10:46,100
expensive both in
terms of compute, cost,

199
00:10:46,100 --> 00:10:50,420
everything part of the training.

200
00:10:50,420 --> 00:10:55,740
So what it does is taking
a huge amount of data

201
00:10:55,740 --> 00:11:01,140
and training your LLM to
just predict the next token.

202
00:11:01,140 --> 00:11:04,700
And here, by data, what I
mean is basically everything

203
00:11:04,700 --> 00:11:06,180
you can find.

204
00:11:06,180 --> 00:11:09,260
So it can be text in English.

205
00:11:09,260 --> 00:11:12,620
It can be text in
other languages.

206
00:11:12,620 --> 00:11:18,020
It can be even code, can be
code in different languages,

207
00:11:18,020 --> 00:11:20,820
can be basically
the whole internet.

208
00:11:20,820 --> 00:11:24,220
We're going to see
some of the data sets

209
00:11:24,220 --> 00:11:27,260
that people use for that,
but you can think of this

210
00:11:27,260 --> 00:11:31,740
as just training your model to
try to predict anything that's

211
00:11:31,740 --> 00:11:34,500
written.

212
00:11:34,500 --> 00:11:37,440
And as I mentioned,
the objective here

213
00:11:37,440 --> 00:11:40,400
is to predict the next token.

214
00:11:40,400 --> 00:11:45,040
So if you remember, our
LLM is a text-to-text model

215
00:11:45,040 --> 00:11:48,720
and most likely a decoder
only model in more than 90%

216
00:11:48,720 --> 00:11:49,840
of the cases.

217
00:11:49,840 --> 00:11:53,940
So what it does is it
takes some input text,

218
00:11:53,940 --> 00:11:57,680
and it tries to always
predict the next token

219
00:11:57,680 --> 00:12:01,040
in an iterative basis.

220
00:12:01,040 --> 00:12:03,840
So in terms of the data
sets that are used,

221
00:12:03,840 --> 00:12:08,080
you will see the term Common
Crawl a lot on papers.

222
00:12:08,080 --> 00:12:11,280
It's basically a data
set composed of anything

223
00:12:11,280 --> 00:12:13,440
you can find on the internet.

224
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:17,040
So I think they have something
like three billion pages

225
00:12:17,040 --> 00:12:18,560
per month.

226
00:12:18,560 --> 00:12:22,720
So if you go on their website,
they have a huge archive.

227
00:12:22,720 --> 00:12:24,440
So there's a bunch
of other websites

228
00:12:24,440 --> 00:12:25,900
as well that you
can find in there.

229
00:12:25,900 --> 00:12:29,440
So for instance, Wikipedia
articles, any social media

230
00:12:29,440 --> 00:12:30,720
as well, like Reddit.

231
00:12:30,720 --> 00:12:33,900
And there are a lot of Reddit
conversations in those data

232
00:12:33,900 --> 00:12:34,400
sets.

233
00:12:34,400 --> 00:12:36,420
You have a lot of codes,
and of course, you

234
00:12:36,420 --> 00:12:37,960
have a bunch of places for that.

235
00:12:37,960 --> 00:12:41,140
You have GitHub, you have Stack
Overflow, all these forums

236
00:12:41,140 --> 00:12:42,620
that talk about codes.

237
00:12:42,620 --> 00:12:45,260
So all of this is
meant for your model

238
00:12:45,260 --> 00:12:48,830
to just understand the structure
of the language and code.

239
00:12:51,900 --> 00:12:55,140
And in terms of size, so
it's measured in terms

240
00:12:55,140 --> 00:12:57,260
of tokens, number of tokens.

241
00:12:57,260 --> 00:13:00,340
And one order of magnitude
that I want you to remember

242
00:13:00,340 --> 00:13:04,900
is on the order of
hundreds of billions

243
00:13:04,900 --> 00:13:09,993
or even trillions or even
tens of trillions of tokens.

244
00:13:09,993 --> 00:13:11,160
So I'll give you an example.

245
00:13:11,160 --> 00:13:14,800
So GPT-3 was trained
on 300 billion tokens.

246
00:13:14,800 --> 00:13:16,780
And for instance,
Llama 3, which was

247
00:13:16,780 --> 00:13:19,660
I believe published
last year, was

248
00:13:19,660 --> 00:13:23,340
trained on 15 trillion tokens.

249
00:13:23,340 --> 00:13:24,890
So these are huge data sets.

250
00:13:27,740 --> 00:13:33,400
So before we go further, I want
to introduce two notations.

251
00:13:33,400 --> 00:13:38,720
And I think one of them I
introduced it last lecture.

252
00:13:38,720 --> 00:13:41,440
The reason why I want to talk
to you about these notations

253
00:13:41,440 --> 00:13:45,400
is they're used everywhere
to talk about how

254
00:13:45,400 --> 00:13:49,840
much compute some model needs.

255
00:13:49,840 --> 00:13:53,880
So the first notation
is FLOPs, which

256
00:13:53,880 --> 00:13:57,240
stands for floating operations.

257
00:13:57,240 --> 00:14:01,800
And what it is it's
a unit of compute.

258
00:14:01,800 --> 00:14:06,800
So the higher the FLOPs, the
more operations are involved.

259
00:14:06,800 --> 00:14:09,400
Because by definition,
FLOPs is the number

260
00:14:09,400 --> 00:14:13,760
of operations that involve
floating point numbers.

261
00:14:13,760 --> 00:14:15,760
So floating point numbers,
you can think of them

262
00:14:15,760 --> 00:14:19,760
as just numbers
with decimal points.

263
00:14:19,760 --> 00:14:23,200
So in terms of order
of magnitudes, training

264
00:14:23,200 --> 00:14:30,360
an LLM is on the order of
10 to the power of 25 FLOPs.

265
00:14:30,360 --> 00:14:33,620
And the way you obtain
FLOPs, so usually, it's

266
00:14:33,620 --> 00:14:35,000
a complicated formula.

267
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:37,500
But in your mind,
you can think of it

268
00:14:37,500 --> 00:14:42,240
as something that is a function
of the size of your data,

269
00:14:42,240 --> 00:14:45,820
so the number of tokens
that you train it on,

270
00:14:45,820 --> 00:14:49,500
and the number of
parameters of your model.

271
00:14:49,500 --> 00:14:51,460
So there's not an
universal formula

272
00:14:51,460 --> 00:14:55,260
because it also is a
function of the architecture.

273
00:14:55,260 --> 00:15:00,300
So you can think, for instance,
MOE based LLMs as requiring,

274
00:15:00,300 --> 00:15:02,780
let's say, less compute
because only some parts are

275
00:15:02,780 --> 00:15:08,780
activated compared to,
let's say, dense LLMs.

276
00:15:08,780 --> 00:15:10,940
But you can just
think of it as it's

277
00:15:10,940 --> 00:15:13,240
a function of the number
of tokens and parameters.

278
00:15:13,240 --> 00:15:19,220
It's like O of the product
between the two, more or less.

279
00:15:19,220 --> 00:15:21,820
And then there's
a second notation

280
00:15:21,820 --> 00:15:24,900
that I want to introduce,
which is also FLOPS,

281
00:15:24,900 --> 00:15:26,700
but it's different.

282
00:15:26,700 --> 00:15:31,160
So here, FLOPS stands for
floating point operations

283
00:15:31,160 --> 00:15:34,120
per second.

284
00:15:34,120 --> 00:15:38,280
So it's a measure
of compute speeds.

285
00:15:38,280 --> 00:15:42,880
So it's basically how
fast can your hardware

286
00:15:42,880 --> 00:15:46,000
execute these operations.

287
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:49,440
And so you also have some
order of magnitudes here.

288
00:15:49,440 --> 00:15:53,040
But if you're into,
let's say GPUs,

289
00:15:53,040 --> 00:15:55,440
you will see that in
the description of GPUs,

290
00:15:55,440 --> 00:15:59,000
they always indicate FLOPS.

291
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:01,760
And we will see
that in a second.

292
00:16:01,760 --> 00:16:06,760
But I just want to call out
that FLOPS here is usually

293
00:16:06,760 --> 00:16:12,720
all caps, although you may
see some papers that use one

294
00:16:12,720 --> 00:16:16,320
for the other,
which is confusing.

295
00:16:16,320 --> 00:16:23,000
So I'll just recommend just
contextualizing this notation

296
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:25,760
with respect to the sentence
that it is in because sometimes

297
00:16:25,760 --> 00:16:27,440
people actually switch the two.

298
00:16:27,440 --> 00:16:31,380
But this is the common notation.

299
00:16:31,380 --> 00:16:34,020
So far, so good?

300
00:16:34,020 --> 00:16:36,620
Cool.

301
00:16:36,620 --> 00:16:40,150
So now, we know that we
have a pre-training step.

302
00:16:40,150 --> 00:16:42,630
We know it involves
a lot of compute.

303
00:16:42,630 --> 00:16:44,506
We know it involves
a lot of data.

304
00:16:44,506 --> 00:16:47,100
We know our model is large.

305
00:16:47,100 --> 00:16:50,860
So what people did
was trying to see

306
00:16:50,860 --> 00:16:56,860
how the performance evolves
as a function of model size

307
00:16:56,860 --> 00:16:59,980
and training size.

308
00:16:59,980 --> 00:17:02,740
And there is this one
paper called Scaling Loss

309
00:17:02,740 --> 00:17:06,220
for Neural Language Models
that was published in 2020

310
00:17:06,220 --> 00:17:09,500
that performed a
bunch of experiments

311
00:17:09,500 --> 00:17:11,660
by varying these parameters.

312
00:17:11,660 --> 00:17:16,300
And what they found was
the more compute you have,

313
00:17:16,300 --> 00:17:20,579
the better your model learns
about predicting the next token.

314
00:17:20,579 --> 00:17:23,000
Same for data set size.

315
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:28,640
So the bigger your training
set, the better it is,

316
00:17:28,640 --> 00:17:33,520
and the bigger your
model, the better it is.

317
00:17:33,520 --> 00:17:39,080
So for some time, I think,
between 2019 and 2024,

318
00:17:39,080 --> 00:17:42,340
you were seeing models that
were larger and larger,

319
00:17:42,340 --> 00:17:44,160
just people just
building things that

320
00:17:44,160 --> 00:17:49,640
were bigger and bigger because
according to these experiments,

321
00:17:49,640 --> 00:17:53,440
the performance was
just getting better.

322
00:17:53,440 --> 00:17:55,800
So something else
that they noticed

323
00:17:55,800 --> 00:18:00,440
was bigger models
tend to be more

324
00:18:00,440 --> 00:18:03,920
what they call sample efficient.

325
00:18:03,920 --> 00:18:08,160
So what that means is for
an equal amount of tokens

326
00:18:08,160 --> 00:18:11,760
that is processed,
you will have a better

327
00:18:11,760 --> 00:18:16,420
performance with a bigger model
compared to a smaller one.

328
00:18:19,720 --> 00:18:25,580
But then you can wonder, we
don't have unlimited compute.

329
00:18:25,580 --> 00:18:27,180
Compute is expensive.

330
00:18:27,180 --> 00:18:29,560
It has a lot of drawbacks.

331
00:18:29,560 --> 00:18:36,020
So you have a fixed
compute, and people also

332
00:18:36,020 --> 00:18:42,140
try to answer the question given
a certain amount of compute,

333
00:18:42,140 --> 00:18:47,660
how can you fix your training
set size and your model size

334
00:18:47,660 --> 00:18:50,420
in a way that's more optimal?

335
00:18:50,420 --> 00:18:55,180
Because here, you need to
decide how big is your model.

336
00:18:55,180 --> 00:18:59,140
So what they did is they
fixed a unit of compute, which

337
00:18:59,140 --> 00:19:02,340
is the color of these curves.

338
00:19:02,340 --> 00:19:07,020
And they tried training
models of different sizes

339
00:19:07,020 --> 00:19:10,260
with different
training set size.

340
00:19:10,260 --> 00:19:16,300
And what they saw was that there
was always a sweet spot here,

341
00:19:16,300 --> 00:19:23,080
which followed some kind of
relationship, and in particular,

342
00:19:23,080 --> 00:19:26,140
this is a table that
summarizes, quote unquote,

343
00:19:26,140 --> 00:19:30,240
"the optimal set of number of
parameters and training set

344
00:19:30,240 --> 00:19:33,720
size," which is sometimes
called the Chinchilla law.

345
00:19:33,720 --> 00:19:41,000
And what they realized was if
you have an amount of training

346
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:46,680
set size that's about
20 times the model size,

347
00:19:46,680 --> 00:19:51,120
then you're spending your
compute in a, quote unquote,

348
00:19:51,120 --> 00:19:53,000
"an optimal way."

349
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:58,160
And in particular,
GPT-3, for instance, I

350
00:19:58,160 --> 00:20:02,260
think it was like 175
billion parameters,

351
00:20:02,260 --> 00:20:04,320
if I remember
correctly, but it's only

352
00:20:04,320 --> 00:20:06,920
trained on 300 billion tokens.

353
00:20:06,920 --> 00:20:11,040
So this one, for instance,
is, according to this,

354
00:20:11,040 --> 00:20:14,532
"really undertrained,"
quote unquote.

355
00:20:14,532 --> 00:20:15,740
I think there was a question.

356
00:20:15,740 --> 00:20:16,240
Yeah.

357
00:20:16,240 --> 00:20:20,016
[AUDIO OUT]

358
00:20:26,980 --> 00:20:27,560
So yeah.

359
00:20:27,560 --> 00:20:29,768
The question is, do they
fit the neural architecture?

360
00:20:29,768 --> 00:20:33,180
So I think by now,
everyone agrees

361
00:20:33,180 --> 00:20:38,460
that LLMs are transformer-based
decoder only models.

362
00:20:38,460 --> 00:20:42,540
So everyone uses the same model.

363
00:20:42,540 --> 00:20:45,560
So you can assume that
when I say LLM here,

364
00:20:45,560 --> 00:20:48,770
it basically means decoder
only transformer-based models.

365
00:20:48,770 --> 00:20:53,640
[AUDIO OUT]

366
00:20:53,640 --> 00:20:54,140
Yeah.

367
00:20:54,140 --> 00:20:56,560
Question is architecture change
does not play a big role.

368
00:20:56,560 --> 00:20:57,960
So that's what they say
actually in their paper.

369
00:20:57,960 --> 00:20:59,627
They say the thing
that changes the most

370
00:20:59,627 --> 00:21:01,565
is the amount of tokens
on which you train

371
00:21:01,565 --> 00:21:02,690
and the size of your model.

372
00:21:05,580 --> 00:21:06,080
Cool.

373
00:21:06,080 --> 00:21:08,200
Any other questions?

374
00:21:08,200 --> 00:21:08,700
Yeah.

375
00:21:08,700 --> 00:21:13,065
[AUDIO OUT]

376
00:21:23,760 --> 00:21:24,317
Oh, yeah.

377
00:21:24,317 --> 00:21:24,900
Good question.

378
00:21:24,900 --> 00:21:26,480
So question is,
is there some kind

379
00:21:26,480 --> 00:21:30,400
of transfer learning between
different versions of models?

380
00:21:30,400 --> 00:21:33,080
So for a lot of these models,
they're actually closed source.

381
00:21:33,080 --> 00:21:34,980
So they don't exactly
reveal these things.

382
00:21:34,980 --> 00:21:39,880
But I guess it's an
interesting question,

383
00:21:39,880 --> 00:21:42,060
one that I cannot
answer in a general way.

384
00:21:42,060 --> 00:21:45,440
So maybe I think it's the
best answer I can give you.

385
00:21:45,440 --> 00:21:50,500
But in any case, when you
look at some of these papers,

386
00:21:50,500 --> 00:21:53,860
they always state how much
it costs to train this.

387
00:21:53,860 --> 00:21:57,020
And it's always in
the order of millions.

388
00:21:57,020 --> 00:22:01,920
It's always an expensive
step regardless.

389
00:22:01,920 --> 00:22:03,560
Cool.

390
00:22:03,560 --> 00:22:06,640
Just speaking of
that, so pre-training

391
00:22:06,640 --> 00:22:07,740
has a lot of challenges.

392
00:22:07,740 --> 00:22:09,600
One of them is cost.

393
00:22:09,600 --> 00:22:12,860
So when I say, millions
of dollars, it's minimum.

394
00:22:12,860 --> 00:22:15,280
I think it can even cost
tens of millions of dollars

395
00:22:15,280 --> 00:22:18,420
or sometimes hundreds
of millions of dollars.

396
00:22:18,420 --> 00:22:23,340
It takes a lot of
time, and people

397
00:22:23,340 --> 00:22:26,440
have been mindful of the
impact on the environment.

398
00:22:26,440 --> 00:22:30,900
So they've also been including
the ecological costs.

399
00:22:30,900 --> 00:22:37,060
So the other challenge is
that the pre-training step

400
00:22:37,060 --> 00:22:42,580
is on data that is up to the
time at which you pre-train

401
00:22:42,580 --> 00:22:44,380
your model on.

402
00:22:44,380 --> 00:22:48,780
So what that means is that
the knowledge that you acquire

403
00:22:48,780 --> 00:22:52,260
from training on this
data set can only

404
00:22:52,260 --> 00:23:00,020
go up until the date at
which you cut your data set.

405
00:23:00,020 --> 00:23:04,340
So this date is called
the knowledge cutoff date.

406
00:23:04,340 --> 00:23:07,640
And so what that means
is your base model,

407
00:23:07,640 --> 00:23:11,220
your pre-trained
base model has no way

408
00:23:11,220 --> 00:23:17,880
to know by itself knowledge
that occurred after this date.

409
00:23:17,880 --> 00:23:20,200
And speaking of that,
a lot of papers,

410
00:23:20,200 --> 00:23:22,960
they have tried to edit
knowledge, inject knowledge.

411
00:23:22,960 --> 00:23:26,760
It's always tricky because
there's not a clean way

412
00:23:26,760 --> 00:23:30,680
to change the
weights in a way that

413
00:23:30,680 --> 00:23:34,480
does not penalize some parts.

414
00:23:34,480 --> 00:23:36,040
So I guess what
people want to do

415
00:23:36,040 --> 00:23:40,380
is inject knowledge but not
regress in some other domains.

416
00:23:40,380 --> 00:23:43,160
And this is a very hard problem.

417
00:23:43,160 --> 00:23:44,880
And of course,
these models, they

418
00:23:44,880 --> 00:23:47,080
try to predict the next token.

419
00:23:47,080 --> 00:23:50,440
And there's this
question of what

420
00:23:50,440 --> 00:23:53,680
if it just generates
something that it

421
00:23:53,680 --> 00:23:54,980
has seen at training time?

422
00:23:54,980 --> 00:23:57,160
So what we call plagiarism.

423
00:23:57,160 --> 00:23:59,057
So there's always a risk.

424
00:23:59,057 --> 00:24:00,640
So these are all the
challenges I just

425
00:24:00,640 --> 00:24:04,020
want to illustrate when I
said knowledge cutoff date.

426
00:24:04,020 --> 00:24:08,040
So if you go on, let's say,
the OpenAI website or Google

427
00:24:08,040 --> 00:24:12,580
website to look at the model
cards, you will always see--

428
00:24:12,580 --> 00:24:14,320
so I'm not sure as
you can see from here,

429
00:24:14,320 --> 00:24:19,860
but there is always a line on
knowledge cutoff date, which

430
00:24:19,860 --> 00:24:23,060
tells you on when the
pre-training of this model

431
00:24:23,060 --> 00:24:24,300
was done.

432
00:24:24,300 --> 00:24:28,160
So here, for instance, GPT-5
was released a few weeks ago,

433
00:24:28,160 --> 00:24:32,020
and here, it says, the knowledge
cutoff date is September 30.

434
00:24:32,020 --> 00:24:35,700
So you can guess that they've
done their pre-training

435
00:24:35,700 --> 00:24:36,450
around that stage.

436
00:24:39,300 --> 00:24:40,900
Cool.

437
00:24:40,900 --> 00:24:45,380
Any questions on the first part?

438
00:24:45,380 --> 00:24:47,540
All good?

439
00:24:47,540 --> 00:24:48,500
Perfect.

440
00:24:48,500 --> 00:24:51,660
So in this first
part, we've seen

441
00:24:51,660 --> 00:24:56,660
that pre-training was a crucial
step of the LLM training

442
00:24:56,660 --> 00:24:57,860
process.

443
00:24:57,860 --> 00:25:01,300
And we've seen all
these big numbers.

444
00:25:01,300 --> 00:25:06,780
And one could wonder, well, how
can you train such a big model

445
00:25:06,780 --> 00:25:09,320
on such a big amount of data?

446
00:25:09,320 --> 00:25:12,440
How do people do that?

447
00:25:12,440 --> 00:25:16,000
So this is what we're
going to see here.

448
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:19,100
So this is what I mentioned.

449
00:25:19,100 --> 00:25:24,280
So LLMs, you can think
of them as decoder only

450
00:25:24,280 --> 00:25:26,360
transformer-based models.

451
00:25:26,360 --> 00:25:30,840
So in order to train your
model, you need that.

452
00:25:30,840 --> 00:25:35,120
You need a lot of
data, but then if you

453
00:25:35,120 --> 00:25:40,960
look at your architecture, you
see that a lot of the operations

454
00:25:40,960 --> 00:25:44,240
involve matrix multiplications.

455
00:25:44,240 --> 00:25:46,040
And I guess I have
a question for you.

456
00:25:46,040 --> 00:25:47,520
What is the kind
of hardware that

457
00:25:47,520 --> 00:25:51,720
loves matrix multiplications?

458
00:25:51,720 --> 00:25:52,320
GPUs.

459
00:25:52,320 --> 00:25:52,920
Yes.

460
00:25:52,920 --> 00:25:54,800
So you also need GPUs.

461
00:25:54,800 --> 00:25:56,740
Actually more than one.

462
00:25:56,740 --> 00:25:57,240
Yeah.

463
00:25:57,240 --> 00:25:58,032
You had a question.

464
00:25:58,032 --> 00:26:00,440
[AUDIO OUT]

465
00:26:03,200 --> 00:26:03,720
Oh.

466
00:26:03,720 --> 00:26:05,020
Question is GPT for inference.

467
00:26:05,020 --> 00:26:07,080
So this one, we're going
to focus on training,

468
00:26:07,080 --> 00:26:10,540
but requirements for GPUs,
they differ a little bit

469
00:26:10,540 --> 00:26:13,260
between training and
inference, but in this part,

470
00:26:13,260 --> 00:26:16,660
we're solely
focused on training.

471
00:26:16,660 --> 00:26:20,157
And speaking of GPUs, I guess,
it's not GPUs everywhere

472
00:26:20,157 --> 00:26:21,740
because, for instance,
Google, they've

473
00:26:21,740 --> 00:26:25,380
developed their own
hardware that's called TPUs,

474
00:26:25,380 --> 00:26:30,740
but any non Google-based
models, they've most likely

475
00:26:30,740 --> 00:26:33,900
been trained on GPUs.

476
00:26:33,900 --> 00:26:34,520
Cool.

477
00:26:34,520 --> 00:26:37,740
So in order to train your
model, what do you do?

478
00:26:37,740 --> 00:26:41,340
So first of all,
you have your LLM

479
00:26:41,340 --> 00:26:43,160
which is now-- so
it is this model,

480
00:26:43,160 --> 00:26:46,900
but now, we're representing
with a box just for simplicity.

481
00:26:46,900 --> 00:26:48,500
You initialize it.

482
00:26:48,500 --> 00:26:51,120
It's a lot of parameters.

483
00:26:51,120 --> 00:26:55,540
So you can think of the scale as
being somewhere around billions

484
00:26:55,540 --> 00:26:59,900
to hundreds of billions of
parameters, so huge model.

485
00:26:59,900 --> 00:27:03,700
And what are the steps
involved to train a model?

486
00:27:03,700 --> 00:27:08,960
Well, what you're trying to
do is to tune the weights,

487
00:27:08,960 --> 00:27:14,640
so that the model can learn
how to generate the next token.

488
00:27:14,640 --> 00:27:17,760
So you have one step called
the forward pass, where

489
00:27:17,760 --> 00:27:20,520
you have a bunch of
data that you're trying

490
00:27:20,520 --> 00:27:22,600
to pass through the network.

491
00:27:22,600 --> 00:27:25,760
And while we do
that, I just want

492
00:27:25,760 --> 00:27:30,760
to call out things that are
important to note that we

493
00:27:30,760 --> 00:27:33,680
need to somehow save in memory.

494
00:27:33,680 --> 00:27:35,420
So when you do
this forward pass,

495
00:27:35,420 --> 00:27:38,920
you have something that's called
activations, which are basically

496
00:27:38,920 --> 00:27:45,000
the values at each layer that
are needed in order to compute

497
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:46,720
the loss.

498
00:27:46,720 --> 00:27:48,800
So the loss tells
you how off you

499
00:27:48,800 --> 00:27:53,280
are compared to the label that
you want to train this on.

500
00:27:53,280 --> 00:27:56,120
And so the amount of memory
that you will use here

501
00:27:56,120 --> 00:27:57,740
is dependent on a lot of things.

502
00:27:57,740 --> 00:28:00,320
It's dependent on the
model size, which impacts

503
00:28:00,320 --> 00:28:01,960
the number of activations.

504
00:28:01,960 --> 00:28:07,140
It's dependent on how big your
batch of data is for training.

505
00:28:07,140 --> 00:28:10,840
And it's dependent on how
large your context length is,

506
00:28:10,840 --> 00:28:17,540
because if you remember, here we
have O of N squared complexity

507
00:28:17,540 --> 00:28:19,780
because of this
self-attention operation,

508
00:28:19,780 --> 00:28:21,820
where N is the sequence length.

509
00:28:21,820 --> 00:28:26,540
So you have all these
parameters that come into play.

510
00:28:26,540 --> 00:28:28,260
So once you do the
forward pass, let's

511
00:28:28,260 --> 00:28:30,440
suppose you compute the loss.

512
00:28:30,440 --> 00:28:34,380
You know how off you are
compared to your label.

513
00:28:34,380 --> 00:28:38,220
Now, the next step
is to somehow tweak

514
00:28:38,220 --> 00:28:43,540
the weights in a way
that minimizes the loss.

515
00:28:43,540 --> 00:28:44,520
So how do you do that?

516
00:28:44,520 --> 00:28:47,980
There is this another pass
called backwards pass.

517
00:28:47,980 --> 00:28:54,620
So what this pass does
is quantify the direction

518
00:28:54,620 --> 00:28:58,460
where the loss is
going to be minimized.

519
00:28:58,460 --> 00:28:59,760
It's called the gradient.

520
00:28:59,760 --> 00:29:02,220
You take the gradient
of the loss with respect

521
00:29:02,220 --> 00:29:04,760
to each parameter.

522
00:29:04,760 --> 00:29:10,200
Well, gradients, they also need
to be saved somewhere in memory.

523
00:29:10,200 --> 00:29:13,640
And then you have finally
the weights update,

524
00:29:13,640 --> 00:29:18,400
which is where you know where
the direction at which your loss

525
00:29:18,400 --> 00:29:19,460
is going to be minimized.

526
00:29:19,460 --> 00:29:22,320
So you apply that
update to your weights.

527
00:29:22,320 --> 00:29:26,680
And you typically use
optimizers out there.

528
00:29:26,680 --> 00:29:29,160
Have you heard of
Adam optimizer?

529
00:29:29,160 --> 00:29:30,040
Yeah.

530
00:29:30,040 --> 00:29:32,320
So Adam optimizer is
just a fancy version

531
00:29:32,320 --> 00:29:36,400
that has some additional
quantities, which

532
00:29:36,400 --> 00:29:38,680
keep track of--

533
00:29:38,680 --> 00:29:41,040
which are basically a
function of the gradients.

534
00:29:41,040 --> 00:29:43,340
So you have the first moment
and the second moment,

535
00:29:43,340 --> 00:29:47,960
which is basically the moving
average of the gradient

536
00:29:47,960 --> 00:29:51,360
and the squared gradients.

537
00:29:51,360 --> 00:29:53,740
And all these quantities,
so the first moment,

538
00:29:53,740 --> 00:29:57,840
the second moment, you also
need to somehow save them

539
00:29:57,840 --> 00:30:00,560
somewhere in memory.

540
00:30:00,560 --> 00:30:03,740
So it's a lot of things to save.

541
00:30:03,740 --> 00:30:05,680
Well, OK.

542
00:30:05,680 --> 00:30:08,080
Breaking news, memory
is not unlimited.

543
00:30:08,080 --> 00:30:09,540
Memory is limited.

544
00:30:09,540 --> 00:30:11,660
And so here, what we
have in front of us

545
00:30:11,660 --> 00:30:16,620
is the description of a GPU.

546
00:30:16,620 --> 00:30:17,180
I think.

547
00:30:17,180 --> 00:30:17,680
Yeah.

548
00:30:17,680 --> 00:30:19,860
H100, which is a very good GPU.

549
00:30:19,860 --> 00:30:23,120
And you will see in
that description,

550
00:30:23,120 --> 00:30:26,180
there's a line on GPU memory.

551
00:30:26,180 --> 00:30:29,460
So GPU memory is your
amount of memory per GPU.

552
00:30:29,460 --> 00:30:32,240
It's 80 gig for this one.

553
00:30:32,240 --> 00:30:33,420
It's quite large.

554
00:30:33,420 --> 00:30:38,380
So it's in on the order
of tens of gigabytes.

555
00:30:38,380 --> 00:30:42,580
So you need to store all these
things in 80 gigabytes, which

556
00:30:42,580 --> 00:30:44,940
is not a lot.

557
00:30:44,940 --> 00:30:48,240
So what are we doing?

558
00:30:48,240 --> 00:30:51,060
What will you be doing?

559
00:30:51,060 --> 00:30:54,340
So I guess the
idea is to leverage

560
00:30:54,340 --> 00:30:59,480
not one but several GPUs in
order to somehow distribute

561
00:30:59,480 --> 00:31:02,000
the load across CPUs.

562
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:06,000
And in order to do that,
you have several methods,

563
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:08,640
which we will see in a second.

564
00:31:08,640 --> 00:31:14,480
So the first set of methods
is called data parallelism,

565
00:31:14,480 --> 00:31:17,720
also known as DP.

566
00:31:17,720 --> 00:31:21,240
So what this set
of methods does is

567
00:31:21,240 --> 00:31:29,040
it distributes data across
GPUs, so that this forward

568
00:31:29,040 --> 00:31:34,520
pass and backward pass, they
can all be done independently.

569
00:31:34,520 --> 00:31:37,320
And so the idea here is to
divide the batch of data

570
00:31:37,320 --> 00:31:43,380
across devices, and then in
order to do that, of course,

571
00:31:43,380 --> 00:31:47,640
you need to have a copy
of the model per device.

572
00:31:47,640 --> 00:31:50,380
Because of course, you need
to compute the activations.

573
00:31:50,380 --> 00:31:53,960
You need to compute
all these things.

574
00:31:53,960 --> 00:31:58,740
But when you do that, you're are
able to reduce the memory that

575
00:31:58,740 --> 00:32:01,835
is linked to the batch size.

576
00:32:01,835 --> 00:32:03,400
So that's called
data parallelism.

577
00:32:03,400 --> 00:32:03,900
Yes.

578
00:32:07,300 --> 00:32:09,560
Question is how about
the gradient update?

579
00:32:09,560 --> 00:32:11,160
Well, it's a great question.

580
00:32:11,160 --> 00:32:16,060
So what do you do when you have
independent computations here

581
00:32:16,060 --> 00:32:17,140
and there?

582
00:32:17,140 --> 00:32:19,420
Well, the gradient
is just the average

583
00:32:19,420 --> 00:32:22,080
of the gradients for this thing.

584
00:32:22,080 --> 00:32:25,740
So you have some communication
in between the GPUs

585
00:32:25,740 --> 00:32:31,020
that basically aggregates
the gradient for the updates.

586
00:32:31,020 --> 00:32:33,660
So I have a question for you.

587
00:32:33,660 --> 00:32:37,220
Is this the answer
to everything?

588
00:32:37,220 --> 00:32:39,700
If we just scale
up like this for,

589
00:32:39,700 --> 00:32:43,720
I don't know, a lot of GPUs,
is it great, always great

590
00:32:43,720 --> 00:32:44,970
or do we have cons?

591
00:32:48,260 --> 00:32:49,060
Oh, yeah.

592
00:32:49,060 --> 00:32:49,640
Great point.

593
00:32:49,640 --> 00:32:51,320
So yeah, you have
to fit one model.

594
00:32:51,320 --> 00:32:52,960
So yeah, this is a great point.

595
00:32:52,960 --> 00:32:54,800
So the second point
that I will add

596
00:32:54,800 --> 00:32:58,040
is you have an
additional cost, which

597
00:32:58,040 --> 00:33:00,000
is called communication
cost, because you

598
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:03,800
need to somehow communicate
between your GPUs

599
00:33:03,800 --> 00:33:07,360
in order to aggregate
some quantities.

600
00:33:07,360 --> 00:33:09,840
So your training is
going to be slower.

601
00:33:09,840 --> 00:33:10,540
It's good.

602
00:33:10,540 --> 00:33:11,940
You can scale up the memory.

603
00:33:11,940 --> 00:33:16,520
Of course, you need to
fit a model on a device,

604
00:33:16,520 --> 00:33:18,940
and we will see
how we to do that.

605
00:33:18,940 --> 00:33:24,180
But you will be incurring
those communication costs,

606
00:33:24,180 --> 00:33:27,680
so it's not all great.

607
00:33:27,680 --> 00:33:30,600
So speaking of the
memory and the fact

608
00:33:30,600 --> 00:33:34,720
that we want to, I guess,
be able to at least

609
00:33:34,720 --> 00:33:38,700
store a model per device.

610
00:33:38,700 --> 00:33:42,600
So people have realized
that there's actually

611
00:33:42,600 --> 00:33:45,920
a lot of duplication.

612
00:33:45,920 --> 00:33:50,200
And there has been
a paper on wanting

613
00:33:50,200 --> 00:33:54,900
to deduplicate this
duplicate information

614
00:33:54,900 --> 00:34:01,500
and this method is called ZeRO,
ZeRO redundancy optimization.

615
00:34:01,500 --> 00:34:08,100
And the idea is
that on each GPU,

616
00:34:08,100 --> 00:34:11,800
you store the same parameters,
you store the same gradients,

617
00:34:11,800 --> 00:34:17,020
you store the same
optimizer states.

618
00:34:17,020 --> 00:34:23,620
So the idea here is how
about we shard, we partition

619
00:34:23,620 --> 00:34:26,340
those quantities across GPUs?

620
00:34:26,340 --> 00:34:31,960
So the first variation is around
sharing the optimizer state.

621
00:34:31,960 --> 00:34:36,260
So meaning, we partition
those states across the GPUs.

622
00:34:36,260 --> 00:34:39,100
So this reduces the
memory by a lot.

623
00:34:39,100 --> 00:34:43,060
We can also partition
the gradients,

624
00:34:43,060 --> 00:34:46,500
and we can also
partition the parameters.

625
00:34:46,500 --> 00:34:50,420
So here, we have no
redundant information.

626
00:34:50,420 --> 00:34:52,440
Things are just partitioned.

627
00:34:52,440 --> 00:34:54,000
Well, the problem
is you're going

628
00:34:54,000 --> 00:34:57,800
to have even more
communication costs,

629
00:34:57,800 --> 00:35:03,520
but at least it allows for
us to decrease the memory

630
00:35:03,520 --> 00:35:04,630
load on each GPU.

631
00:35:07,280 --> 00:35:11,420
So this is ZeRO, so there's
ZeRO 1, ZeRO 2, ZeRO 3.

632
00:35:11,420 --> 00:35:13,600
And I guess the
variation that you

633
00:35:13,600 --> 00:35:19,600
will choose will be a function
of how sensitive you are to,

634
00:35:19,600 --> 00:35:25,520
I guess, training time
and how big is your model

635
00:35:25,520 --> 00:35:27,420
and whether this will
be an actual problem,

636
00:35:27,420 --> 00:35:32,200
or are you just fine with
just storing everything?

637
00:35:32,200 --> 00:35:35,320
So that's one set of methods.

638
00:35:35,320 --> 00:35:39,000
So this set of methods is,
again, data parallelism.

639
00:35:39,000 --> 00:35:45,320
So it's basically you having
independent sets of data that

640
00:35:45,320 --> 00:35:49,060
are handled by different GPUs.

641
00:35:49,060 --> 00:35:52,060
Well, you have another
set of methods that's

642
00:35:52,060 --> 00:35:55,700
called model parallelism.

643
00:35:55,700 --> 00:36:01,660
So model parallelism tries to
parallelize the operation even

644
00:36:01,660 --> 00:36:04,700
within one batch.

645
00:36:04,700 --> 00:36:06,780
So there's a bunch of methods.

646
00:36:06,780 --> 00:36:08,880
I don't want to sound
too like a catalog.

647
00:36:08,880 --> 00:36:12,380
So we're not going through
them all but one by one.

648
00:36:12,380 --> 00:36:16,180
But I will just call out a
few that are worth noting.

649
00:36:16,180 --> 00:36:20,980
So if you remember last lecture,
we talked about MOE-based LLMs

650
00:36:20,980 --> 00:36:27,220
and how sequences were being
sent to different experts.

651
00:36:27,220 --> 00:36:30,460
Well, there is a way
to distribute that

652
00:36:30,460 --> 00:36:36,660
across GPUs via this expert
parallelism techniques, which

653
00:36:36,660 --> 00:36:40,780
is having, let's say, one
expert on a device, another one

654
00:36:40,780 --> 00:36:42,980
on another device.

655
00:36:42,980 --> 00:36:45,500
So that's one
thing worth noting.

656
00:36:45,500 --> 00:36:48,320
Another one, I will say,
so a tensor parallelism

657
00:36:48,320 --> 00:36:54,240
is when you have big matrix
multiplications to somehow cut

658
00:36:54,240 --> 00:37:00,760
that in a way that decreases
the memory required for that.

659
00:37:00,760 --> 00:37:04,800
And maybe the last one I will
say is pipeline parallelism.

660
00:37:04,800 --> 00:37:08,800
It's when you consider
a forward pass

661
00:37:08,800 --> 00:37:11,680
as involving several layers.

662
00:37:11,680 --> 00:37:14,640
So you're going to say that
one GPU is going to only

663
00:37:14,640 --> 00:37:17,960
be responsible for, let's
say, layers 1 to 3 and then

664
00:37:17,960 --> 00:37:19,520
another one layer 3--

665
00:37:19,520 --> 00:37:25,880
sorry, 4 to 5, 4, 5, 6,
and so on and so forth.

666
00:37:25,880 --> 00:37:27,920
So you also have that
kind of parallelism.

667
00:37:27,920 --> 00:37:30,120
But anyways, there's
a bunch of techniques.

668
00:37:30,120 --> 00:37:32,400
And the ones that
I mentioned they

669
00:37:32,400 --> 00:37:35,980
fall in the bucket
of model parallelism.

670
00:37:38,960 --> 00:37:41,640
Make sense?

671
00:37:41,640 --> 00:37:43,700
No need to know the
details on there.

672
00:37:43,700 --> 00:37:46,240
But I think just knowing that
there are several methods

673
00:37:46,240 --> 00:37:52,620
and just a rough idea, I think,
is a good thing to have in mind.

674
00:37:52,620 --> 00:37:54,360
Cool.

675
00:37:54,360 --> 00:37:55,780
So what did we do?

676
00:37:55,780 --> 00:37:59,820
So we realized that during
the training process,

677
00:37:59,820 --> 00:38:02,500
we had to save a lot
of things in memory.

678
00:38:02,500 --> 00:38:06,060
So what we saw was
techniques that

679
00:38:06,060 --> 00:38:10,280
reduce the burden of
having memory per GPU,

680
00:38:10,280 --> 00:38:13,640
so we are trying to
distribute that across GPUs.

681
00:38:13,640 --> 00:38:17,500
So we saw data
parallelism and then

682
00:38:17,500 --> 00:38:21,480
the ZeRO method that has
some extra optimizations.

683
00:38:21,480 --> 00:38:25,900
And we saw model
parallelism as well.

684
00:38:25,900 --> 00:38:31,220
So now, we're going to see
another technique that leverages

685
00:38:31,220 --> 00:38:33,540
the structure of the GPU.

686
00:38:33,540 --> 00:38:35,800
And you may have heard
of this technique.

687
00:38:35,800 --> 00:38:39,020
It's called flash attention.

688
00:38:39,020 --> 00:38:44,520
It was actually developed
here at Stanford in 2022.

689
00:38:44,520 --> 00:38:49,040
And in order for me to talk
to you about this technique,

690
00:38:49,040 --> 00:38:54,680
I want to tell you more about
what the GPU is composed of.

691
00:38:54,680 --> 00:38:57,600
So if you look under the hood--

692
00:38:57,600 --> 00:39:01,008
well, GPU is very complicated
and I'm for sure not--

693
00:39:01,008 --> 00:39:02,300
I don't know everything either.

694
00:39:02,300 --> 00:39:08,200
But what I know is that we have
two kinds of memories in GPU.

695
00:39:08,200 --> 00:39:14,480
So you have one kind of memory
that's big but relatively slow.

696
00:39:14,480 --> 00:39:17,280
That's in the HBM.

697
00:39:17,280 --> 00:39:21,540
And then another kind of
memory that is fast but much,

698
00:39:21,540 --> 00:39:26,880
much smaller, which is
on chip next to where

699
00:39:26,880 --> 00:39:28,200
the compute happens.

700
00:39:28,200 --> 00:39:30,400
That's called the SRAM.

701
00:39:30,400 --> 00:39:33,880
So you have HBM and SRAM.

702
00:39:33,880 --> 00:39:37,980
HBM has something around
tens of gigabytes.

703
00:39:37,980 --> 00:39:41,668
So it's like the GPU memory
that you saw in the description.

704
00:39:41,668 --> 00:39:44,000
SRAM is much smaller.

705
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:48,840
It's like something around
several tens of megabytes

706
00:39:48,840 --> 00:39:49,660
let's say.

707
00:39:49,660 --> 00:39:54,760
So it's much smaller, but
then it is 10 times faster.

708
00:39:54,760 --> 00:40:00,340
So this one is a few terabytes
per second let's say.

709
00:40:00,340 --> 00:40:04,660
And the SRAM is tens of
terabytes per second.

710
00:40:04,660 --> 00:40:08,860
So it's a noticeable
difference in speed.

711
00:40:08,860 --> 00:40:13,260
So what we want is
to somehow leverage

712
00:40:13,260 --> 00:40:17,180
the strength of these
kinds of memories

713
00:40:17,180 --> 00:40:19,100
in order to speed
up the attention

714
00:40:19,100 --> 00:40:22,620
computation in an exact way.

715
00:40:22,620 --> 00:40:24,380
So what do I mean by exact way?

716
00:40:24,380 --> 00:40:28,860
So what I mean is we're not
making any approximations

717
00:40:28,860 --> 00:40:31,540
to the computation.

718
00:40:31,540 --> 00:40:34,500
What we're doing is
we're just leveraging

719
00:40:34,500 --> 00:40:38,940
the strength of these components
and sending the computation

720
00:40:38,940 --> 00:40:42,200
in a clever way.

721
00:40:42,200 --> 00:40:47,400
So if you remember, the
self-attention computation

722
00:40:47,400 --> 00:40:52,480
is done with this very
important formula.

723
00:40:52,480 --> 00:40:55,360
So it's softmax of
queries and keys

724
00:40:55,360 --> 00:41:00,120
over some scaling
factor times V.

725
00:41:00,120 --> 00:41:06,480
So this allows queries to
interact with everyone else.

726
00:41:06,480 --> 00:41:12,080
So in matrix form, you
can think of queries

727
00:41:12,080 --> 00:41:15,600
as having the number of rows
equal to the sequence length.

728
00:41:15,600 --> 00:41:19,540
And then columns to being
the dimension of the query.

729
00:41:19,540 --> 00:41:21,740
And then same for key and value.

730
00:41:21,740 --> 00:41:26,120
So you have this big
matrix multiplications.

731
00:41:26,120 --> 00:41:28,000
So if you do it--

732
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:31,240
if you do this
computation, the standards

733
00:41:31,240 --> 00:41:34,440
the vanilla way,
what you would do

734
00:41:34,440 --> 00:41:40,740
is store them in the
big but slow memory

735
00:41:40,740 --> 00:41:43,140
component of the GPU.

736
00:41:43,140 --> 00:41:46,860
So you would store
it in the HBM.

737
00:41:46,860 --> 00:41:49,020
So here is what you
would do if you were

738
00:41:49,020 --> 00:41:50,440
to not do any optimization.

739
00:41:50,440 --> 00:41:59,340
So you would take those matrices
from the big but slow HBM,

740
00:41:59,340 --> 00:42:06,020
perform the computation, and
then write it back to the HBM.

741
00:42:06,020 --> 00:42:10,300
And then you would read that
result again from the HBM,

742
00:42:10,300 --> 00:42:16,900
compute the softmax, and then
write it back to the HBM.

743
00:42:16,900 --> 00:42:22,660
And then you would again load
this plus the value matrix,

744
00:42:22,660 --> 00:42:26,540
multiply them, and then
write them to the HBM.

745
00:42:26,540 --> 00:42:30,480
See, there's a lot read
and write to the HBM.

746
00:42:30,480 --> 00:42:34,620
So it's a lot of data
transfer, which actually

747
00:42:34,620 --> 00:42:36,600
becomes the bottleneck.

748
00:42:36,600 --> 00:42:41,000
So a GPU is very, very fast,
but then you spend a lot of time

749
00:42:41,000 --> 00:42:45,720
just loading your
matrices from the memory.

750
00:42:45,720 --> 00:42:50,440
The reason why you do that
is because of this softmax

751
00:42:50,440 --> 00:42:51,835
operation.

752
00:42:51,835 --> 00:42:53,460
So do you remember
what a softmax does?

753
00:42:53,460 --> 00:42:59,240
So it normalizes the quantities,
so that they sum to 1.

754
00:42:59,240 --> 00:43:04,240
But it's row dependent
meaning that each row needs

755
00:43:04,240 --> 00:43:07,280
to sum up to 1.

756
00:43:07,280 --> 00:43:10,760
So in a sense, you need that
computation to happen first

757
00:43:10,760 --> 00:43:13,760
before you do your softmax.

758
00:43:13,760 --> 00:43:17,120
If you just look
at it like that,

759
00:43:17,120 --> 00:43:20,210
you would think, yeah, you need
to do the whole thing first.

760
00:43:22,760 --> 00:43:25,960
Well, it turns
out that you don't

761
00:43:25,960 --> 00:43:30,000
need to do everything at once.

762
00:43:30,000 --> 00:43:34,900
And this is the core idea
behind flash attention.

763
00:43:34,900 --> 00:43:38,060
So what flash
attention does is it

764
00:43:38,060 --> 00:43:41,900
tries to minimize
the amount of read

765
00:43:41,900 --> 00:43:48,940
and write from and to the HBM
and instead takes small blocks--

766
00:43:48,940 --> 00:43:51,900
and it's called tiling, the
method is called tiling.

767
00:43:51,900 --> 00:43:56,900
It takes small blocks
that it sends to the SRAM,

768
00:43:56,900 --> 00:43:59,380
so that it gets
computed from end

769
00:43:59,380 --> 00:44:02,450
to end before being
sent back to the HBM.

770
00:44:05,340 --> 00:44:07,340
Does that make sense?

771
00:44:07,340 --> 00:44:14,420
So the idea is let's send
small matrices into the SRAM,

772
00:44:14,420 --> 00:44:18,820
so that it does the whole
full end-to-end computation

773
00:44:18,820 --> 00:44:21,380
and just send it
back to the HBM,

774
00:44:21,380 --> 00:44:23,500
because we want to
minimize the amount read

775
00:44:23,500 --> 00:44:26,260
and write from the HBM.

776
00:44:26,260 --> 00:44:28,160
So here is how you would do it.

777
00:44:28,160 --> 00:44:32,000
So you remember, the
softmax computation

778
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:34,720
with the query and the
key and then the value.

779
00:44:34,720 --> 00:44:41,320
Well, what you would do
is to cut your matrices

780
00:44:41,320 --> 00:44:46,080
and then proceed step by step.

781
00:44:46,080 --> 00:44:47,720
But then there's a
cool trick that I

782
00:44:47,720 --> 00:44:49,880
want to talk to
you about, which is

783
00:44:49,880 --> 00:44:54,800
that you don't need to
compute the whole matrix

784
00:44:54,800 --> 00:44:59,320
inside a softmax in order
to achieve the whole softmax

785
00:44:59,320 --> 00:45:01,320
computation.

786
00:45:01,320 --> 00:45:03,360
Because if you think
about it, let's suppose

787
00:45:03,360 --> 00:45:05,800
you have a whole matrix,
and then you have different,

788
00:45:05,800 --> 00:45:09,600
let's say, columns or
submatrices, S1 to SN,

789
00:45:09,600 --> 00:45:14,240
well, softmax of
this huge matrix

790
00:45:14,240 --> 00:45:19,720
is equal to this matrix,
where the softmax is taken

791
00:45:19,720 --> 00:45:22,640
with respect to each
of these submatrices

792
00:45:22,640 --> 00:45:26,560
up to some scaling factor.

793
00:45:26,560 --> 00:45:29,240
So this is the core trick.

794
00:45:29,240 --> 00:45:31,160
And if you want to
be convinced of it,

795
00:45:31,160 --> 00:45:33,000
just look at the
softmax formula,

796
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:36,860
it's exponential of something
over some quantity, which

797
00:45:36,860 --> 00:45:39,660
is shared across the row.

798
00:45:39,660 --> 00:45:47,460
So this scaling factor will just
fix this with respect to that.

799
00:45:47,460 --> 00:45:50,860
So with this in
mind, what we will do

800
00:45:50,860 --> 00:45:57,660
is take each respective
slices of this matrices,

801
00:45:57,660 --> 00:46:01,220
do the whole computation,
and then populate

802
00:46:01,220 --> 00:46:07,540
the corresponding entry
in the output matrix.

803
00:46:07,540 --> 00:46:10,100
So we will do that
between, let's say,

804
00:46:10,100 --> 00:46:12,340
the first slice of the
query and the first slice

805
00:46:12,340 --> 00:46:14,340
of the keys and the values.

806
00:46:14,340 --> 00:46:19,380
And then we will repeat for
the other slice until the end.

807
00:46:19,380 --> 00:46:21,860
And then we will repeat
for the other queries

808
00:46:21,860 --> 00:46:26,140
as well until the end.

809
00:46:26,140 --> 00:46:31,760
So what the paper explains
is how this scaling factor

810
00:46:31,760 --> 00:46:33,290
is being computed.

811
00:46:33,290 --> 00:46:36,540
So this one is some formula
that I did not put on the slide,

812
00:46:36,540 --> 00:46:40,100
so it's not necessary for
you to memorize the formula.

813
00:46:40,100 --> 00:46:42,160
It's just the idea.

814
00:46:42,160 --> 00:46:43,910
And the idea is
exactly this trick.

815
00:46:47,480 --> 00:46:52,400
So once you do that,
you basically end up

816
00:46:52,400 --> 00:46:57,240
with only one read from the HPM.

817
00:46:57,240 --> 00:47:02,400
And these [INAUDIBLE] quantities
are stored in the SRAM.

818
00:47:02,400 --> 00:47:04,200
And then they're read
from the SRAM, which

819
00:47:04,200 --> 00:47:09,200
is very fast, and then computed,
and then back to the SRAM.

820
00:47:09,200 --> 00:47:13,580
And then at the end, in order
to accumulate the results,

821
00:47:13,580 --> 00:47:18,320
they're being sent
back to the HBM.

822
00:47:18,320 --> 00:47:19,740
So just to make
sure we're clear.

823
00:47:19,740 --> 00:47:23,720
So in green, it's basically
when it's read from SRAM,

824
00:47:23,720 --> 00:47:25,447
and then in blue,
it's from the HBM.

825
00:47:25,447 --> 00:47:26,280
You have a question?

826
00:47:26,280 --> 00:47:26,780
Yeah.

827
00:47:26,780 --> 00:47:29,400
[AUDIO OUT]

828
00:47:41,557 --> 00:47:44,140
The question is, do you take the
whole row or a portion of it?

829
00:47:44,140 --> 00:47:45,640
So you can take a portion of it.

830
00:47:45,640 --> 00:47:47,280
But just for
illustrative purposes,

831
00:47:47,280 --> 00:47:49,240
here we take the exclusive.

832
00:47:49,240 --> 00:47:51,340
This is just for
illustrative purposes.

833
00:47:51,340 --> 00:47:56,760
You can think of your matrix
as being completely a grid.

834
00:47:56,760 --> 00:47:59,400
And then you just
multiply accordingly.

835
00:47:59,400 --> 00:48:01,680
But yeah, this is just
for illustrative purposes.

836
00:48:01,680 --> 00:48:02,180
Yeah.

837
00:48:12,800 --> 00:48:13,300
Yeah.

838
00:48:13,300 --> 00:48:15,882
So the question is,
are you computing alpha

839
00:48:15,882 --> 00:48:17,340
and all these
quantities on the fly

840
00:48:17,340 --> 00:48:18,632
or do you have some estimation?

841
00:48:18,632 --> 00:48:20,900
So all of this is
exact, and they're

842
00:48:20,900 --> 00:48:23,200
computed in an iterative basis.

843
00:48:23,200 --> 00:48:30,520
So the way it works is when
you populate the output,

844
00:48:30,520 --> 00:48:34,040
you will keep on having
some extra quantity that

845
00:48:34,040 --> 00:48:36,720
will adjust for that.

846
00:48:36,720 --> 00:48:40,338
Think of it as just
some formula that works.

847
00:48:40,338 --> 00:48:42,380
So yeah, I highly recommend
looking at the paper.

848
00:48:42,380 --> 00:48:44,580
They actually explicit
that quite a lot.

849
00:48:44,580 --> 00:48:46,560
So the paper is
Flash Attention, fast

850
00:48:46,560 --> 00:48:49,820
and memory efficient exact
attention with IO awareness.

851
00:48:49,820 --> 00:48:51,940
All of the links
are in the slides.

852
00:48:51,940 --> 00:48:53,360
But yeah, I highly
recommend just

853
00:48:53,360 --> 00:48:57,620
looking at the exact formula in
case you want to be convinced.

854
00:48:57,620 --> 00:48:58,120
Cool.

855
00:48:58,120 --> 00:48:59,790
But the idea makes
sense overall?

856
00:49:02,600 --> 00:49:03,940
Any questions on this?

857
00:49:06,840 --> 00:49:08,400
Cool.

858
00:49:08,400 --> 00:49:13,480
Well, this was flash
attention, but there's actually

859
00:49:13,480 --> 00:49:15,017
another idea from the paper.

860
00:49:15,017 --> 00:49:16,600
So this was only the
first idea, which

861
00:49:16,600 --> 00:49:23,580
was around making the
attention computation faster.

862
00:49:23,580 --> 00:49:27,500
The second idea is given that
the attention computation is

863
00:49:27,500 --> 00:49:32,660
faster, now let's
try to be smarter

864
00:49:32,660 --> 00:49:37,835
about the backwards pass,
because when you compute

865
00:49:37,835 --> 00:49:39,460
in the backwards
pass, when you compute

866
00:49:39,460 --> 00:49:43,180
the gradient of the loss
with respect to a parameter,

867
00:49:43,180 --> 00:49:49,100
the chain rule will surface
some activations that you

868
00:49:49,100 --> 00:49:52,180
need to have in memory.

869
00:49:52,180 --> 00:49:58,580
Well, here, given that computing
these activations is very fast,

870
00:49:58,580 --> 00:50:02,980
one idea is to just
not store activations

871
00:50:02,980 --> 00:50:07,940
from the forward pass or at
least not store everything,

872
00:50:07,940 --> 00:50:10,660
but instead in the
backwards pass,

873
00:50:10,660 --> 00:50:12,650
compute these activations again.

874
00:50:15,860 --> 00:50:18,060
So it's called
the recomputation.

875
00:50:18,060 --> 00:50:20,880
So when you do the forward
pass, you compute an activation

876
00:50:20,880 --> 00:50:23,600
to be able to compute
the loss, but then

877
00:50:23,600 --> 00:50:29,800
instead of saving it to reuse
it during the gradient update,

878
00:50:29,800 --> 00:50:32,440
you will just
discard it and then

879
00:50:32,440 --> 00:50:36,000
recompute the activation
during the backwards pass

880
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:41,320
with this very fast technique.

881
00:50:41,320 --> 00:50:45,080
And when you do that, it's
actually quite remarkable.

882
00:50:45,080 --> 00:50:48,040
So you do more operations.

883
00:50:48,040 --> 00:50:51,340
So gigaFLOPs is just
a derivative of FLOPs.

884
00:50:51,340 --> 00:50:53,472
So it's the number of
operations you're doing.

885
00:50:53,472 --> 00:50:55,680
So with flash attention,
you're doing more operations

886
00:50:55,680 --> 00:51:00,640
because you're actually
recomputing things.

887
00:51:00,640 --> 00:51:05,420
But then so you also see fewer
read and writes from the HBM.

888
00:51:05,420 --> 00:51:08,880
So here, for instance, it
was 40.3 in the standard way

889
00:51:08,880 --> 00:51:12,480
and then 4 point-- so it's
like almost a 10x reduction.

890
00:51:12,480 --> 00:51:17,960
But then you see that the
runtime is also smaller.

891
00:51:17,960 --> 00:51:20,700
So this is very remarkable
because usually,

892
00:51:20,700 --> 00:51:25,940
when you recompute things,
you are saving memory

893
00:51:25,940 --> 00:51:30,100
but at the expense of runtime.

894
00:51:30,100 --> 00:51:31,440
You're just taking longer.

895
00:51:31,440 --> 00:51:34,317
But here, you're not only
taking less amount of time,

896
00:51:34,317 --> 00:51:35,400
you're also saving memory.

897
00:51:35,400 --> 00:51:37,370
So you're basically
having everything.

898
00:51:37,370 --> 00:51:40,660
It's the best of all worlds.

899
00:51:40,660 --> 00:51:43,280
So this is what flash
attention mentioned.

900
00:51:43,280 --> 00:51:46,920
So you will see that there
are some other, I guess,

901
00:51:46,920 --> 00:51:48,200
variants of flash attention.

902
00:51:48,200 --> 00:51:50,740
So flash attention
2, flash attention 3.

903
00:51:50,740 --> 00:51:56,860
And I would say that these are
more adaptation of these methods

904
00:51:56,860 --> 00:52:01,020
to the current infra,
because each new GPU comes

905
00:52:01,020 --> 00:52:06,540
with new pros and cons, so
strengths and weaknesses.

906
00:52:06,540 --> 00:52:08,900
And I guess there's
always a way to make

907
00:52:08,900 --> 00:52:12,073
these optimizations better.

908
00:52:12,073 --> 00:52:13,740
But yeah, I would say
flash attention is

909
00:52:13,740 --> 00:52:20,310
quite a common trick, and I
think it's a very good thing to.

910
00:52:20,310 --> 00:52:21,310
So does that make sense?

911
00:52:25,680 --> 00:52:26,400
Cool.

912
00:52:26,400 --> 00:52:28,920
I'll take that as a yes.

913
00:52:28,920 --> 00:52:29,420
OK.

914
00:52:29,420 --> 00:52:30,160
Cool.

915
00:52:30,160 --> 00:52:32,240
OK, so last thing--

916
00:52:32,240 --> 00:52:36,020
no, we have a few things that
I want to talk to you about.

917
00:52:36,020 --> 00:52:40,960
So you have your LLM
with a bunch of weights.

918
00:52:40,960 --> 00:52:43,720
These weights are
all floating points.

919
00:52:43,720 --> 00:52:45,760
So you can think of
them as just being

920
00:52:45,760 --> 00:52:49,680
numbers with a bunch of
numbers after the decimal.

921
00:52:49,680 --> 00:52:52,080
One natural question
you can ask yourself

922
00:52:52,080 --> 00:52:57,440
is, do you really need to
know that much precision

923
00:52:57,440 --> 00:53:01,160
after the decimal point to
be able to do a good job?

924
00:53:01,160 --> 00:53:03,600
I guess put another
way, can you just

925
00:53:03,600 --> 00:53:08,100
cut your precision in
some way to save on memory

926
00:53:08,100 --> 00:53:11,520
but then keep the
same performance?

927
00:53:11,520 --> 00:53:15,180
So this is the idea
behind quantization.

928
00:53:15,180 --> 00:53:19,580
So quantization is the
process of converting

929
00:53:19,580 --> 00:53:22,400
the precision of a
number from, let's say,

930
00:53:22,400 --> 00:53:27,020
one setting to another.

931
00:53:27,020 --> 00:53:28,680
In order to better
understand that,

932
00:53:28,680 --> 00:53:33,100
I think it's important to
know how floating points--

933
00:53:33,100 --> 00:53:40,260
sorry, floating point
numbers, how they are encoded.

934
00:53:40,260 --> 00:53:46,020
So in practice, they're
just a bunch of bits.

935
00:53:46,020 --> 00:53:49,260
And here, you have some bits
that are responsible for,

936
00:53:49,260 --> 00:53:50,940
let's say, the
exponent, some that

937
00:53:50,940 --> 00:53:53,820
are responsible for the
mantissa, which is basically

938
00:53:53,820 --> 00:53:57,180
how granular your number is.

939
00:53:57,180 --> 00:54:00,980
And then one that
is about the sign.

940
00:54:00,980 --> 00:54:04,260
So you have a bunch of
representations of floats.

941
00:54:04,260 --> 00:54:06,520
So the most common
ones are in this table.

942
00:54:06,520 --> 00:54:12,970
So you have so single point
precision, half precision,

943
00:54:12,970 --> 00:54:16,650
floating point
64, brain float 16

944
00:54:16,650 --> 00:54:21,330
that are each having different
granularities for the three

945
00:54:21,330 --> 00:54:23,290
dimensions.

946
00:54:23,290 --> 00:54:25,690
So if we take the
first two rows, which

947
00:54:25,690 --> 00:54:28,770
are the two most common
representations that you will

948
00:54:28,770 --> 00:54:36,850
see out there, floating point 16
is only represented on 16 bits

949
00:54:36,850 --> 00:54:38,890
compared to 32.

950
00:54:38,890 --> 00:54:41,490
So it takes basically
half the memory

951
00:54:41,490 --> 00:54:43,930
if you want to think
about it this way.

952
00:54:43,930 --> 00:54:47,610
But then it's less precise,
meaning it's less granular.

953
00:54:47,610 --> 00:54:50,450
So I guess one
idea that we could

954
00:54:50,450 --> 00:54:55,570
have is to somehow decrease the
granularity of these weights

955
00:54:55,570 --> 00:55:00,250
and these numbers, hoping that
it will not impact performance

956
00:55:00,250 --> 00:55:03,130
too much.

957
00:55:03,130 --> 00:55:05,650
So another thing that
I want to mention

958
00:55:05,650 --> 00:55:10,310
is back to that GPU description.

959
00:55:10,310 --> 00:55:14,790
You see that there is also
a bunch of information

960
00:55:14,790 --> 00:55:17,147
around the compute speed.

961
00:55:17,147 --> 00:55:19,230
So I'm not sure if you can
see very well on there.

962
00:55:19,230 --> 00:55:20,688
Can you see very
well on the slide?

963
00:55:20,688 --> 00:55:21,910
So I'll read it.

964
00:55:21,910 --> 00:55:26,350
The compute speed as a function
of which representation

965
00:55:26,350 --> 00:55:27,090
you're using.

966
00:55:27,090 --> 00:55:30,070
So here, if you're
using FP64, which

967
00:55:30,070 --> 00:55:34,070
is this super granular way
of representing numbers,

968
00:55:34,070 --> 00:55:38,250
you only have 34 teraFLOPs
of compute speed.

969
00:55:38,250 --> 00:55:39,870
But then if you're
using a, let's say,

970
00:55:39,870 --> 00:55:46,870
FP32, which is half of it, you
can double your compute speed

971
00:55:46,870 --> 00:55:47,530
and so on.

972
00:55:47,530 --> 00:55:52,110
You have all these
other numbers as well.

973
00:55:52,110 --> 00:55:54,330
So the idea is you
can save on memory.

974
00:55:54,330 --> 00:55:56,120
You can also go faster.

975
00:55:59,470 --> 00:56:02,030
So with this in
mind, I just want

976
00:56:02,030 --> 00:56:04,550
to touch on one last
technique before giving it

977
00:56:04,550 --> 00:56:09,530
to Shervin, which is
mixed precision training.

978
00:56:09,530 --> 00:56:13,090
So the idea behind
mixed precision training

979
00:56:13,090 --> 00:56:17,490
is to leverage different
granularities of float

980
00:56:17,490 --> 00:56:21,530
representations such
that it will not

981
00:56:21,530 --> 00:56:27,930
hurt the performance too much
but allow you to save on memory

982
00:56:27,930 --> 00:56:31,930
and do things faster.

983
00:56:31,930 --> 00:56:34,810
So the idea behind
mixed precision training

984
00:56:34,810 --> 00:56:40,170
is you have your models or
you have your model, you

985
00:56:40,170 --> 00:56:46,730
keep your weights in
high precision, so FP32,

986
00:56:46,730 --> 00:56:48,770
and all the
operations that you do

987
00:56:48,770 --> 00:56:50,690
in the forward
and backward pass,

988
00:56:50,690 --> 00:56:53,490
you're going to do it
in a lower precision.

989
00:56:53,490 --> 00:56:56,650
So in this case, FP16.

990
00:56:56,650 --> 00:57:02,260
But then the weight updates
will be done still in FP32.

991
00:57:04,810 --> 00:57:08,210
So the authors of the
paper, when they did that,

992
00:57:08,210 --> 00:57:10,710
basically what they
realized was the performance

993
00:57:10,710 --> 00:57:13,150
was not degraded too much.

994
00:57:13,150 --> 00:57:15,510
But then you had a lot
of savings on memory

995
00:57:15,510 --> 00:57:18,590
and then it was running faster.

996
00:57:18,590 --> 00:57:24,950
So now you may wonder, well,
why are you keeping the weights

997
00:57:24,950 --> 00:57:28,310
at a high precision but not
the activations and so on?

998
00:57:28,310 --> 00:57:32,510
So I can offer you just
a bit of intuition.

999
00:57:32,510 --> 00:57:36,670
So whenever you
perform a forward pass,

1000
00:57:36,670 --> 00:57:39,390
you're performing
that on a set of data.

1001
00:57:39,390 --> 00:57:43,710
But that set of data
can be noisy in itself.

1002
00:57:43,710 --> 00:57:48,030
So maybe all the
decimal points after--

1003
00:57:48,030 --> 00:57:50,190
so all the numbers
after the decimal point

1004
00:57:50,190 --> 00:57:53,230
may not be as useful.

1005
00:57:53,230 --> 00:57:56,630
So you can think of this update
as being more in which direction

1006
00:57:56,630 --> 00:58:00,110
should the weights go
to a more optimal state.

1007
00:58:00,110 --> 00:58:05,090
So it doesn't require
them to be super precise,

1008
00:58:05,090 --> 00:58:08,290
but then it's much more
important to keep your weights,

1009
00:58:08,290 --> 00:58:11,730
so the weights of the model
in high precision in order

1010
00:58:11,730 --> 00:58:18,530
to not accumulate errors
due to quantization.

1011
00:58:18,530 --> 00:58:21,210
That's one way just
think about it.

1012
00:58:21,210 --> 00:58:23,010
But the long story
short is if you

1013
00:58:23,010 --> 00:58:27,410
reduce the granularity
of some numbers,

1014
00:58:27,410 --> 00:58:30,290
then you will have
a lot of benefits

1015
00:58:30,290 --> 00:58:33,630
and not a lot of disadvantages
in terms of the performance.

1016
00:58:36,810 --> 00:58:38,370
Cool.

1017
00:58:38,370 --> 00:58:38,870
Yeah.

1018
00:58:52,210 --> 00:58:53,230
That's a great question.

1019
00:58:53,230 --> 00:58:56,210
So the question is, do
you apply this technique

1020
00:58:56,210 --> 00:59:01,010
to all weights of all layers
or just to some of them?

1021
00:59:01,010 --> 00:59:03,470
So there has been a
lot of papers on that.

1022
00:59:03,470 --> 00:59:07,990
And the answer is there
are some variations to it.

1023
00:59:07,990 --> 00:59:10,710
And so the answer
is not necessarily.

1024
00:59:10,710 --> 00:59:11,970
So I do have some pointers.

1025
00:59:11,970 --> 00:59:13,690
Happy to share them with you.

1026
00:59:13,690 --> 00:59:18,990
But some parts may be more
important than others.

1027
00:59:18,990 --> 00:59:23,290
So this strategy is a little
bit a high level idea,

1028
00:59:23,290 --> 00:59:27,300
but there are always some
variations from setup to setup.

1029
00:59:30,090 --> 00:59:30,590
Yeah.

1030
00:59:35,910 --> 00:59:40,270
So is your question that
people rely on the relationship

1031
00:59:40,270 --> 00:59:41,630
between compute--

1032
00:59:41,630 --> 00:59:44,070
and sorry, not compute,
parameters and token

1033
00:59:44,070 --> 00:59:47,030
from the Chinchilla
paper, but it

1034
00:59:47,030 --> 00:59:49,883
may be different from
their setup which

1035
00:59:49,883 --> 00:59:52,300
may introduce something-- this
is basically your question?

1036
01:00:01,050 --> 01:00:03,050
So the question
is, is there also

1037
01:00:03,050 --> 01:00:05,590
an optimal precision to use?

1038
01:00:05,590 --> 01:00:08,030
So I would say, people
use different things.

1039
01:00:08,030 --> 01:00:11,410
There's not like a set way
where everyone does something.

1040
01:00:11,410 --> 01:00:15,850
But I would say that these
scaling, like this Chinchilla

1041
01:00:15,850 --> 01:00:19,610
law, is actually something
that some authors,

1042
01:00:19,610 --> 01:00:24,810
they try to reproduce
for their own model.

1043
01:00:24,810 --> 01:00:28,170
So actually, for instance,
the Llama 3 paper,

1044
01:00:28,170 --> 01:00:31,250
there's a whole
part around trying

1045
01:00:31,250 --> 01:00:36,810
to have some relationship
between given

1046
01:00:36,810 --> 01:00:41,530
a fixed amount of compute, what
is the optimal number of tokens

1047
01:00:41,530 --> 01:00:46,130
and then a number of parameters
that is unique to their setup.

1048
01:00:46,130 --> 01:00:50,130
So what people do is they
do this thing themselves

1049
01:00:50,130 --> 01:00:55,330
on a small amount of training
set and on smaller models,

1050
01:00:55,330 --> 01:00:57,010
so that it doesn't
cost them too much.

1051
01:00:57,010 --> 01:01:00,750
They try to see what the
relationship is for their setup,

1052
01:01:00,750 --> 01:01:03,110
and then they extrapolate.

1053
01:01:03,110 --> 01:01:04,930
And I believe
that's how Llama 3--

1054
01:01:04,930 --> 01:01:06,510
so I think there's
a model that--

1055
01:01:06,510 --> 01:01:09,670
so Llama 3, 405
billion parameters.

1056
01:01:09,670 --> 01:01:11,830
I think they had the whole
section just justifying

1057
01:01:11,830 --> 01:01:14,230
that they came up to this
number with some experiments

1058
01:01:14,230 --> 01:01:15,010
that they run.

1059
01:01:15,010 --> 01:01:18,070
So to your question,
I think it highly

1060
01:01:18,070 --> 01:01:20,450
depends on the kind of model
that someone is training.

1061
01:01:20,450 --> 01:01:24,790
And they'll probably
have this analysis,

1062
01:01:24,790 --> 01:01:28,910
I guess, with respect
to their own setup.

1063
01:01:28,910 --> 01:01:31,010
Does that answer your question?

1064
01:01:31,010 --> 01:01:31,510
Cool.

1065
01:01:31,510 --> 01:01:33,270
Cool.

1066
01:01:33,270 --> 01:01:33,770
OK.

1067
01:01:33,770 --> 01:01:33,930
Great.

1068
01:01:33,930 --> 01:01:34,430
Yeah.

1069
01:01:49,030 --> 01:01:50,590
The question is,
is there something

1070
01:01:50,590 --> 01:01:51,970
you can do about the range?

1071
01:01:51,970 --> 01:01:53,810
So there are several
types of quantization.

1072
01:01:53,810 --> 01:01:55,670
We're not going
into details here,

1073
01:01:55,670 --> 01:02:00,170
but I can give you a ZeRO
point quantization and absmax

1074
01:02:00,170 --> 01:02:02,530
quantization, which are
different techniques that

1075
01:02:02,530 --> 01:02:04,490
play with these ranges.

1076
01:02:04,490 --> 01:02:06,170
There's also
quantization technique

1077
01:02:06,170 --> 01:02:10,222
that Shervin will cover
that also talks about that.

1078
01:02:10,222 --> 01:02:11,430
So yeah, stay tuned for this.

1079
01:02:11,430 --> 01:02:14,890
But I think ZeRO point
quantization and absmax are

1080
01:02:14,890 --> 01:02:17,350
ones that maybe you
can look into for this.

1081
01:02:19,890 --> 01:02:21,270
Cool.

1082
01:02:21,270 --> 01:02:23,480
So with that, I'm going
to give it to Shervin.

1083
01:02:27,690 --> 01:02:29,250
Thank you, Afshin.

1084
01:02:29,250 --> 01:02:33,030
So now, we have seen how
a pre-training worked.

1085
01:02:33,030 --> 01:02:37,250
We're going to see together
the next stages of training.

1086
01:02:37,250 --> 01:02:39,690
So as we saw with
Afshin, pre-training

1087
01:02:39,690 --> 01:02:45,690
was a way to build the intuition
to the model about how language

1088
01:02:45,690 --> 01:02:50,970
was constructed and about the
main characteristics of what is

1089
01:02:50,970 --> 01:02:52,310
contained in the training data.

1090
01:02:52,310 --> 01:02:53,850
That is general enough.

1091
01:02:53,850 --> 01:02:59,070
So this is why we had corpuses
that spans huge corpora of texts

1092
01:02:59,070 --> 01:03:01,230
that are typically
of the size of what

1093
01:03:01,230 --> 01:03:02,730
you find on the internet.

1094
01:03:02,730 --> 01:03:07,670
So typically, very large
and raw and conveying

1095
01:03:07,670 --> 01:03:09,990
aspects of language.

1096
01:03:09,990 --> 01:03:12,690
So now, you might
want to ask yourself,

1097
01:03:12,690 --> 01:03:16,528
how can we make such
knowledge actually helpful?

1098
01:03:16,528 --> 01:03:18,070
So this is something
that we're going

1099
01:03:18,070 --> 01:03:21,590
to discuss just in a second.

1100
01:03:21,590 --> 01:03:26,790
But before we discuss about what
could motivate further training,

1101
01:03:26,790 --> 01:03:34,230
I want to come back to some very
simple example that will surface

1102
01:03:34,230 --> 01:03:36,350
what could be such a need.

1103
01:03:36,350 --> 01:03:40,110
So let's take our favorite
example about our teddy bear.

1104
01:03:40,110 --> 01:03:44,090
And let's say, we have a
very practical use case.

1105
01:03:44,090 --> 01:03:47,830
So we have thoroughly
loved our teddy bear.

1106
01:03:47,830 --> 01:03:51,730
But now, it has become a bit
dirty, so we need to wash it.

1107
01:03:51,730 --> 01:03:56,330
And you might want to ask your
favorite LLM if you can put it

1108
01:03:56,330 --> 01:03:57,850
in the washer.

1109
01:03:57,850 --> 01:04:01,010
So with the description
that Afshin mentioned

1110
01:04:01,010 --> 01:04:03,890
of LLM pre-training,
I wanted to ask

1111
01:04:03,890 --> 01:04:06,930
you all what was your
opinion about what

1112
01:04:06,930 --> 01:04:11,130
could the output to this be.

1113
01:04:11,130 --> 01:04:11,820
So any guesses?

1114
01:04:15,950 --> 01:04:16,450
Yep.

1115
01:04:21,130 --> 01:04:23,470
Yeah.

1116
01:04:23,470 --> 01:04:23,970
Yeah.

1117
01:04:23,970 --> 01:04:24,510
Excellent.

1118
01:04:24,510 --> 01:04:25,010
Yeah.

1119
01:04:25,010 --> 01:04:28,110
So the answer, the guess
was maybe another question.

1120
01:04:28,110 --> 01:04:30,970
So I think that is a great guess
that could definitely be it.

1121
01:04:30,970 --> 01:04:34,250
So here, in the example,
we put some other sentence

1122
01:04:34,250 --> 01:04:38,530
that could be likely,
but the gist is the same.

1123
01:04:38,530 --> 01:04:41,530
It has been trained on
next token prediction,

1124
01:04:41,530 --> 01:04:45,610
not being an assistant or
someone that is helpful to you.

1125
01:04:45,610 --> 01:04:48,410
So this is why it
will try to mimic

1126
01:04:48,410 --> 01:04:50,490
what could be the pattern
here and what could

1127
01:04:50,490 --> 01:04:53,710
be potential likely next words.

1128
01:04:53,710 --> 01:04:56,310
So for example, the
example we put here

1129
01:04:56,310 --> 01:05:03,750
is something that relates to how
the teddy bear is composed of.

1130
01:05:03,750 --> 01:05:09,370
And because it's in the
same domain as teddy bear

1131
01:05:09,370 --> 01:05:11,110
and then when you talk
about washer, then

1132
01:05:11,110 --> 01:05:15,190
maybe it has been trained
on data that includes

1133
01:05:15,190 --> 01:05:17,070
materials of teddy bears.

1134
01:05:17,070 --> 01:05:19,270
So that could be it.

1135
01:05:19,270 --> 01:05:22,470
And I have a question
with you all.

1136
01:05:22,470 --> 01:05:25,750
Are you happy with it?

1137
01:05:25,750 --> 01:05:26,550
No.

1138
01:05:26,550 --> 01:05:27,050
Yeah.

1139
01:05:27,050 --> 01:05:28,070
Exactly.

1140
01:05:28,070 --> 01:05:29,910
So this is why
we're going to see

1141
01:05:29,910 --> 01:05:35,430
what we can do with the model
to make it helpful to you.

1142
01:05:35,430 --> 01:05:38,390
And this stage is
called fine tuning.

1143
01:05:38,390 --> 01:05:43,510
So we're going to see
that it enables us to,

1144
01:05:43,510 --> 01:05:48,230
in the general
case of LLMs, make

1145
01:05:48,230 --> 01:05:52,010
the LLM a helpful
assistance, but also,

1146
01:05:52,010 --> 01:05:53,770
if you have a
specific use case, you

1147
01:05:53,770 --> 01:05:57,290
can also use this
technique to tune

1148
01:05:57,290 --> 01:05:59,690
the general representation
of the language

1149
01:05:59,690 --> 01:06:02,170
towards your task of interest.

1150
01:06:02,170 --> 01:06:04,770
But we're going to
focus first on what

1151
01:06:04,770 --> 01:06:09,290
is done for LLMs in general.

1152
01:06:09,290 --> 01:06:12,050
So first, I want to
define some terms.

1153
01:06:12,050 --> 01:06:16,610
So model fine tuning is
commonly known as SFT.

1154
01:06:16,610 --> 01:06:22,530
SFT is short for
supervised fine tuning.

1155
01:06:22,530 --> 01:06:26,830
So the supervised part suggests
that we need some labels.

1156
01:06:26,830 --> 01:06:28,370
And it's actually the case.

1157
01:06:28,370 --> 01:06:31,050
So it's pairs of
inputs and outputs

1158
01:06:31,050 --> 01:06:34,090
that we provide the
model to be trained on.

1159
01:06:34,090 --> 01:06:37,130
And this is why it's
called supervised.

1160
01:06:37,130 --> 01:06:40,370
And then fine tuning
is the term that

1161
01:06:40,370 --> 01:06:44,750
refers to refining the weights
that have been already trained.

1162
01:06:44,750 --> 01:06:47,350
So you start from the
pre-trained weights,

1163
01:06:47,350 --> 01:06:51,350
and you further train the
model on additional data

1164
01:06:51,350 --> 01:06:55,470
to get a fine tuned model.

1165
01:06:55,470 --> 01:07:00,550
And then one interesting
note that I will tell you all

1166
01:07:00,550 --> 01:07:05,710
is that the objective function,
even though it's the same,

1167
01:07:05,710 --> 01:07:09,310
will differ a bit from
the pre-training task.

1168
01:07:09,310 --> 01:07:13,030
So in the pre-training task,
you start with the BOS token,

1169
01:07:13,030 --> 01:07:17,510
beginning of
sentence, and you fit

1170
01:07:17,510 --> 01:07:22,710
all your corpora of data trying
to predict the next token.

1171
01:07:22,710 --> 01:07:26,870
But here, since we have this
supervised fine tuning setup,

1172
01:07:26,870 --> 01:07:30,590
where you want the model to
do something useful in cases

1173
01:07:30,590 --> 01:07:32,870
of interest, so let's
say, when I ask the model

1174
01:07:32,870 --> 01:07:36,950
about washing my teddy bear,
so washing my teddy bear

1175
01:07:36,950 --> 01:07:39,530
is actually an input
that I give to the model.

1176
01:07:39,530 --> 01:07:40,850
It's fixed.

1177
01:07:40,850 --> 01:07:44,410
I don't want the model
to parrot what I say.

1178
01:07:44,410 --> 01:07:47,010
I want the model to be
a helpful assistance

1179
01:07:47,010 --> 01:07:49,570
to what I conditioned it on.

1180
01:07:49,570 --> 01:07:54,810
So in this setup, the
input is not a location

1181
01:07:54,810 --> 01:07:56,990
where you would
predict the next token.

1182
01:07:56,990 --> 01:07:59,290
You would not do
teacher forcing on it

1183
01:07:59,290 --> 01:08:02,290
but rather start from this
input and then predict

1184
01:08:02,290 --> 01:08:04,410
the next token onwards.

1185
01:08:04,410 --> 01:08:06,570
And then you're
going to tune what

1186
01:08:06,570 --> 01:08:09,970
the optimal distribution
of next token

1187
01:08:09,970 --> 01:08:13,810
can be based on this input.

1188
01:08:13,810 --> 01:08:17,450
So any questions on
the overall idea of SFT

1189
01:08:17,450 --> 01:08:21,149
before we dive in a bit deeper?

1190
01:08:21,149 --> 01:08:21,649
Yep.

1191
01:08:24,729 --> 01:08:27,670
So the question is we don't
put a loss over the input.

1192
01:08:27,670 --> 01:08:28,310
That's right.

1193
01:08:28,310 --> 01:08:30,250
So you start from the
input, and you start

1194
01:08:30,250 --> 01:08:31,890
predicting the next token.

1195
01:08:31,890 --> 01:08:34,189
And then the loss calculation
starts from there.

1196
01:08:38,420 --> 01:08:40,729
Everything good?

1197
01:08:40,729 --> 01:08:42,425
OK.

1198
01:08:42,425 --> 01:08:46,790
So what I was just
telling you is

1199
01:08:46,790 --> 01:08:51,550
that SFT can be done to tune
your own task of interest,

1200
01:08:51,550 --> 01:08:53,229
but also, it's
something that is being

1201
01:08:53,229 --> 01:08:58,890
done at one of the main
stages of training LLMs

1202
01:08:58,890 --> 01:09:00,670
as you use it every day.

1203
01:09:00,670 --> 01:09:03,630
And then this transition
from the model

1204
01:09:03,630 --> 01:09:08,870
being a good representation of
language to a useful assistance

1205
01:09:08,870 --> 01:09:13,149
is a subcategory of SFT
called instruction tuning.

1206
01:09:13,149 --> 01:09:15,149
So instruction tuning
comes from the fact

1207
01:09:15,149 --> 01:09:20,270
that we want the model
to answer instructions.

1208
01:09:20,270 --> 01:09:24,430
So now, I'm going to
show with the graph what

1209
01:09:24,430 --> 01:09:29,029
I was just mentioning regarding
predicting the next word.

1210
01:09:29,029 --> 01:09:30,310
So actually, just in a bit.

1211
01:09:30,310 --> 01:09:32,590
First, we're going
to look at the data.

1212
01:09:32,590 --> 01:09:36,550
So with Afshin, we saw
that the composition

1213
01:09:36,550 --> 01:09:39,149
of the data for
pre-training was basically

1214
01:09:39,149 --> 01:09:44,569
the whole internet where you
had sources that were carrying

1215
01:09:44,569 --> 01:09:46,729
knowledge such as Wikipedia.

1216
01:09:46,729 --> 01:09:52,410
And in general, masses
of text of English

1217
01:09:52,410 --> 01:09:56,090
that tells the model about how
English and other languages

1218
01:09:56,090 --> 01:09:58,970
work, as well as coding.

1219
01:09:58,970 --> 01:10:01,410
And here, it's
slightly different.

1220
01:10:01,410 --> 01:10:03,210
For instruction
tuning, we're going

1221
01:10:03,210 --> 01:10:07,770
to look at data that's
presents to the model

1222
01:10:07,770 --> 01:10:12,610
how it can most helpfully
respond to instructions.

1223
01:10:12,610 --> 01:10:16,050
So you can divide this
in several categories.

1224
01:10:16,050 --> 01:10:18,250
So here, we present
some categories

1225
01:10:18,250 --> 01:10:20,990
that could be helpful
to users of LLMs.

1226
01:10:20,990 --> 01:10:23,850
For example, story writing.

1227
01:10:23,850 --> 01:10:26,270
You're interested
in writing a story.

1228
01:10:26,270 --> 01:10:28,810
You give it a set
of instructions,

1229
01:10:28,810 --> 01:10:34,130
and then you have a ground
truth that is attached to it.

1230
01:10:34,130 --> 01:10:39,670
Other examples include a poem
creation, list generation,

1231
01:10:39,670 --> 01:10:43,070
explanation, and many
more that are part

1232
01:10:43,070 --> 01:10:47,030
of the data mixture of SFT.

1233
01:10:47,030 --> 01:10:54,950
So basically, you run all these
supervised fine tuning training

1234
01:10:54,950 --> 01:11:00,430
with the inputs that is given,
and then you train the model

1235
01:11:00,430 --> 01:11:03,150
on predicting the output.

1236
01:11:03,150 --> 01:11:06,650
And I'm going now to
show what it looks like.

1237
01:11:06,650 --> 01:11:09,410
So let's say your
instruction is here.

1238
01:11:09,410 --> 01:11:12,510
So you ask your model
to do something.

1239
01:11:12,510 --> 01:11:14,650
So it could be formulated
in a different way

1240
01:11:14,650 --> 01:11:19,310
but just to keep it
short, I just said, do X.

1241
01:11:19,310 --> 01:11:21,270
And then the yellow
part is where

1242
01:11:21,270 --> 01:11:25,370
you start fitting your
objective function on.

1243
01:11:28,305 --> 01:11:29,180
Does this make sense?

1244
01:11:32,830 --> 01:11:35,330
Great.

1245
01:11:35,330 --> 01:11:39,410
So as I was mentioning,
the data mixture

1246
01:11:39,410 --> 01:11:44,970
includes instruction
geared data.

1247
01:11:44,970 --> 01:11:49,170
So for example, you had
