as a user on how helpful

1493
01:26:00,850 --> 01:26:03,570
a model tends to be subjective.

1494
01:26:03,570 --> 01:26:05,810
So how can you put some
number on it is going

1495
01:26:05,810 --> 01:26:08,350
to be a key topic of interest.

1496
01:26:08,350 --> 01:26:11,310
And then also very
soon, we're going

1497
01:26:11,310 --> 01:26:16,470
to see how to make the
computations not that expensive.

1498
01:26:16,470 --> 01:26:20,330
So Afshin talked about training
optimization techniques.

1499
01:26:20,330 --> 01:26:22,810
But now, when we're at
the fine tuning stage,

1500
01:26:22,810 --> 01:26:26,390
maybe we can go one
step further and see

1501
01:26:26,390 --> 01:26:30,650
what simplification
assumption we could make.

1502
01:26:30,650 --> 01:26:31,150
OK.

1503
01:26:31,150 --> 01:26:31,890
Awesome.

1504
01:26:31,890 --> 01:26:34,510
Now, let's dive into
one of these challenges,

1505
01:26:34,510 --> 01:26:37,030
which was the evaluation part.

1506
01:26:37,030 --> 01:26:43,230
So people have decomposed what
they care about in categories.

1507
01:26:43,230 --> 01:26:45,390
So I'm listing here
some dimensions

1508
01:26:45,390 --> 01:26:48,150
that are evaluated
against and that

1509
01:26:48,150 --> 01:26:50,430
gives some quantitative number.

1510
01:26:50,430 --> 01:26:53,870
So you have a general
language where

1511
01:26:53,870 --> 01:26:59,150
this benchmark that is
popular is generally one score

1512
01:26:59,150 --> 01:27:00,370
that people reports.

1513
01:27:00,370 --> 01:27:06,250
It's a MMLU, which
massive multitask

1514
01:27:06,250 --> 01:27:07,510
language understanding.

1515
01:27:07,510 --> 01:27:11,730
So it has, I think, 50
or so tasks in there

1516
01:27:11,730 --> 01:27:14,390
where the model is
being evaluated against,

1517
01:27:14,390 --> 01:27:17,510
and you have some score
that you can compare with.

1518
01:27:17,510 --> 01:27:20,770
You have benchmarks
on reasoning,

1519
01:27:20,770 --> 01:27:25,610
on math reasoning, as
well as code generation.

1520
01:27:25,610 --> 01:27:27,770
So here, you have all
sorts of acronyms,

1521
01:27:27,770 --> 01:27:29,970
and there is even way more.

1522
01:27:29,970 --> 01:27:35,410
So basically, the
setting up benchmark

1523
01:27:35,410 --> 01:27:38,230
has been one area of research.

1524
01:27:38,230 --> 01:27:41,050
So you always see more
and more benchmark

1525
01:27:41,050 --> 01:27:45,350
coming in because people tend to
optimize for those that exist.

1526
01:27:45,350 --> 01:27:47,610
And then there are
some gaps that might

1527
01:27:47,610 --> 01:27:49,810
be filled by further ones.

1528
01:27:49,810 --> 01:27:57,370
And the GSM 8K stands
for grad school--

1529
01:27:57,370 --> 01:27:59,730
so yeah, grad school math.

1530
01:27:59,730 --> 01:28:03,570
8K stands for the
number of examples.

1531
01:28:03,570 --> 01:28:05,070
Yeah, I think so.

1532
01:28:05,070 --> 01:28:06,850
Or maybe G stands
for something else,

1533
01:28:06,850 --> 01:28:09,690
but it's high school
topics basically.

1534
01:28:12,350 --> 01:28:16,710
And one very interesting
pattern that people

1535
01:28:16,710 --> 01:28:19,470
have seen as these
models came out

1536
01:28:19,470 --> 01:28:22,790
and as they were evaluated
against these benchmarks

1537
01:28:22,790 --> 01:28:26,710
is that sometimes for
the same kind of model,

1538
01:28:26,710 --> 01:28:32,350
you see all of a sudden a
spike in numbers with respect

1539
01:28:32,350 --> 01:28:36,630
to some of these benchmarks
without a clear explanation

1540
01:28:36,630 --> 01:28:38,030
behind it.

1541
01:28:38,030 --> 01:28:40,390
And there is this
paper that I highly

1542
01:28:40,390 --> 01:28:44,190
recommend taking a
look, which explores

1543
01:28:44,190 --> 01:28:49,850
the phenomenon of training on
the test task, not the test set.

1544
01:28:49,850 --> 01:28:51,090
The test task.

1545
01:28:51,090 --> 01:28:56,090
So when you have benchmarks
regarding math reasoning,

1546
01:28:56,090 --> 01:29:00,070
let's say, it matters
a lot if the model has

1547
01:29:00,070 --> 01:29:03,050
been trained on a
data that relates

1548
01:29:03,050 --> 01:29:06,370
to that kind of
reasoning versus not.

1549
01:29:06,370 --> 01:29:10,370
And this is why when you type
in those kinds of benchmarks,

1550
01:29:10,370 --> 01:29:16,490
you will see that there are sets
of so-called auxiliary training

1551
01:29:16,490 --> 01:29:18,690
that can be used
for the model to be

1552
01:29:18,690 --> 01:29:21,130
trained on the same domain.

1553
01:29:21,130 --> 01:29:26,130
And in that way,
it enables the fact

1554
01:29:26,130 --> 01:29:30,730
of comparing models with respect
to that specific capability.

1555
01:29:30,730 --> 01:29:34,250
So what the paper
tries to convey here

1556
01:29:34,250 --> 01:29:37,090
is that if you want to compare
models between each other,

1557
01:29:37,090 --> 01:29:42,130
you need to compare the training
mixture it has been trained on

1558
01:29:42,130 --> 01:29:47,610
and then ensure parity in terms
of training on the test task.

1559
01:29:47,610 --> 01:29:51,210
So you need to make sure that,
for example, the two have

1560
01:29:51,210 --> 01:29:55,010
been trained on the
test task or not.

1561
01:29:55,010 --> 01:29:58,410
And if it's one
and the other not,

1562
01:29:58,410 --> 01:30:02,090
then it might not be a
good thing to compare them.

1563
01:30:02,090 --> 01:30:06,670
It doesn't give you the
intrinsic value of the model.

1564
01:30:06,670 --> 01:30:11,190
So yeah, that's an
interesting phenomenon here.

1565
01:30:11,190 --> 01:30:12,170
Any questions?

1566
01:30:15,770 --> 01:30:16,270
OK.

1567
01:30:16,270 --> 01:30:17,190
Great.

1568
01:30:17,190 --> 01:30:19,150
So we can move on.

1569
01:30:19,150 --> 01:30:20,790
So one thing that I
was mentioning here

1570
01:30:20,790 --> 01:30:23,910
is that it's very hard to
get a sense of how good

1571
01:30:23,910 --> 01:30:27,530
a model is, even with
respect to benchmark scores,

1572
01:30:27,530 --> 01:30:31,350
because oftentimes what happens
is that as they come out,

1573
01:30:31,350 --> 01:30:35,910
people design data
on the training site

1574
01:30:35,910 --> 01:30:40,750
that resembles more what we try
to solve on the benchmark side.

1575
01:30:40,750 --> 01:30:44,350
So sometimes you end up
with models that score great

1576
01:30:44,350 --> 01:30:47,750
everywhere, but you as
a user don't necessarily

1577
01:30:47,750 --> 01:30:50,990
see added value to it.

1578
01:30:50,990 --> 01:30:53,388
And it's not the
fault of models.

1579
01:30:53,388 --> 01:30:54,930
It's not the fault
of the benchmarks.

1580
01:30:54,930 --> 01:31:00,530
It's just that it's very hard
to give a number that conveys

1581
01:31:00,530 --> 01:31:04,010
the value to you of the model.

1582
01:31:04,010 --> 01:31:07,450
So this is why people have
come up with other techniques

1583
01:31:07,450 --> 01:31:11,210
to put a number on
model evaluation.

1584
01:31:11,210 --> 01:31:15,570
And you might have
heard of Chatbots Arena.

1585
01:31:15,570 --> 01:31:19,050
Have any folks heard of it here?

1586
01:31:19,050 --> 01:31:20,050
Yeah.

1587
01:31:20,050 --> 01:31:24,810
So it's a website where
models can be submitted,

1588
01:31:24,810 --> 01:31:29,610
and users come in, and
they ask their questions,

1589
01:31:29,610 --> 01:31:33,130
and they're presented
responses from two models.

1590
01:31:33,130 --> 01:31:36,530
And they're being asked to
judge which one is better.

1591
01:31:36,530 --> 01:31:40,970
And then with some pairwise
computations done on the website

1592
01:31:40,970 --> 01:31:45,050
side, they come up with some
ranking in the end that ranks

1593
01:31:45,050 --> 01:31:49,250
model with respect to, quote
unquote, "user preference."

1594
01:31:49,250 --> 01:31:55,090
So it's a number
that is being put

1595
01:31:55,090 --> 01:31:57,510
on the vibes seen by the user.

1596
01:31:57,510 --> 01:32:00,670
And is it all perfect?

1597
01:32:00,670 --> 01:32:04,550
Actually, no.

1598
01:32:04,550 --> 01:32:08,110
So it suffers from
several issues that are--

1599
01:32:08,110 --> 01:32:11,190
another set of issues that
are hard to deal with.

1600
01:32:11,190 --> 01:32:15,350
So among them, when you have
a new model that comes in,

1601
01:32:15,350 --> 01:32:18,390
you have some noise at
the beginning with respect

1602
01:32:18,390 --> 01:32:22,190
to which other model it's
being compared against.

1603
01:32:22,190 --> 01:32:26,350
And these first few steps
actually influence quite a bit

1604
01:32:26,350 --> 01:32:34,510
the actual ranking, which
makes it a brittle property.

1605
01:32:34,510 --> 01:32:37,670
And there is a
paper that actually

1606
01:32:37,670 --> 01:32:43,430
shows that it's easily possible
to rig such a leaderboard.

1607
01:32:43,430 --> 01:32:46,110
So I'm not sure if there
is any evidence that it

1608
01:32:46,110 --> 01:32:47,370
has been done in the past.

1609
01:32:47,370 --> 01:32:50,910
But you can use
any model, if you

1610
01:32:50,910 --> 01:32:53,910
ask the question,
who are you, it's

1611
01:32:53,910 --> 01:32:55,850
just going to say who it is.

1612
01:32:55,850 --> 01:32:57,550
If you ask ChatGPT, who are you.

1613
01:32:57,550 --> 01:32:59,430
It's going to say,
hey, I'm ChatGPT,

1614
01:32:59,430 --> 01:33:00,970
I'm a helpful assistant.

1615
01:33:00,970 --> 01:33:05,370
And this paper observed on
this very simple property

1616
01:33:05,370 --> 01:33:08,170
that it was able to
detect what model

1617
01:33:08,170 --> 01:33:10,250
was being evaluated against.

1618
01:33:10,250 --> 01:33:13,270
And let's say, you have
an adversarial player,

1619
01:33:13,270 --> 01:33:16,730
it could rig the ranking just
by selecting the right model.

1620
01:33:16,730 --> 01:33:20,090
So it's not foolproof.

1621
01:33:20,090 --> 01:33:24,930
And then on other
aspects, so some

1622
01:33:24,930 --> 01:33:27,270
of the benchmarks that
evaluate these models,

1623
01:33:27,270 --> 01:33:30,650
they're actually
curated by experts

1624
01:33:30,650 --> 01:33:35,050
that know very well about the
target distribution of what

1625
01:33:35,050 --> 01:33:38,010
a given prompt should give.

1626
01:33:38,010 --> 01:33:40,970
So it has a set of guidelines
that says clearly, OK, this

1627
01:33:40,970 --> 01:33:41,750
is factual.

1628
01:33:41,750 --> 01:33:43,550
This is non-factual.

1629
01:33:43,550 --> 01:33:47,290
So they're able to determine
what is good versus bad.

1630
01:33:47,290 --> 01:33:50,530
And you as a user, you
might not know about it.

1631
01:33:50,530 --> 01:33:53,750
Because let's just take the
example of the teddy bear

1632
01:33:53,750 --> 01:33:55,530
that you wanted to
put in the washer,

1633
01:33:55,530 --> 01:33:58,710
if I don't know that I need
to hand wash my teddy bear,

1634
01:33:58,710 --> 01:34:01,870
and if I have a detailed
response regarding

1635
01:34:01,870 --> 01:34:06,870
you need to wash it with
a machine wash cold,

1636
01:34:06,870 --> 01:34:10,910
and I could, as a user,
find these pieces of advice

1637
01:34:10,910 --> 01:34:13,130
helpful because they
are actionable to me.

1638
01:34:13,130 --> 01:34:14,850
But actually, are they factual?

1639
01:34:14,850 --> 01:34:18,110
That is a whole other set
of issues that you as a user

1640
01:34:18,110 --> 01:34:22,550
wouldn't be able to tell
on a lot of queries.

1641
01:34:22,550 --> 01:34:27,310
And another challenge that we
have here is a user preference.

1642
01:34:27,310 --> 01:34:34,510
So who here likes it when there
are emojis in LLM responses?

1643
01:34:34,510 --> 01:34:35,350
Yes?

1644
01:34:35,350 --> 01:34:37,630
No?

1645
01:34:37,630 --> 01:34:38,430
Yeah.

1646
01:34:38,430 --> 01:34:39,790
Personally, I do.

1647
01:34:39,790 --> 01:34:43,550
And I think there
are strong opinions.

1648
01:34:43,550 --> 01:34:45,570
And some people
don't like it at all.

1649
01:34:45,570 --> 01:34:47,810
So they will down
rank such responses.

1650
01:34:47,810 --> 01:34:49,990
But actually, it's something
that the user should

1651
01:34:49,990 --> 01:34:52,590
be able to tell and choose.

1652
01:34:52,590 --> 01:34:54,330
And then the
distribution of people

1653
01:34:54,330 --> 01:34:56,610
who choose the best
model with respect

1654
01:34:56,610 --> 01:34:59,290
to the distribution of
the wider population that

1655
01:34:59,290 --> 01:35:02,450
is going to use
these models is going

1656
01:35:02,450 --> 01:35:05,310
to be different oftentimes.

1657
01:35:05,310 --> 01:35:08,610
And I think the emoji
case is a good example,

1658
01:35:08,610 --> 01:35:10,730
because I think
generally, emojis

1659
01:35:10,730 --> 01:35:13,270
are popular in the
wider population.

1660
01:35:13,270 --> 01:35:16,610
But I think domain experts
might not like it as much.

1661
01:35:16,610 --> 01:35:21,570
So I think that mismatch is
one that you would see here.

1662
01:35:21,570 --> 01:35:25,290
And then the last one I will
mention here is the safety side.

1663
01:35:25,290 --> 01:35:28,290
So you as a user,
you don't really

1664
01:35:28,290 --> 01:35:30,970
like it when a model
rejects your prompts.

1665
01:35:30,970 --> 01:35:33,870
When you ask about something,
and it says, OK, hey, sorry,

1666
01:35:33,870 --> 01:35:35,610
I cannot answer it.

1667
01:35:35,610 --> 01:35:40,490
So there will be a bias towards
responses that actually respond

1668
01:35:40,490 --> 01:35:44,610
to your query, rather than
respect some safety principle

1669
01:35:44,610 --> 01:35:49,510
that might be eventually the
intended product decision.

1670
01:35:49,510 --> 01:35:54,070
So there is also this kind
of bias that pops up here.

1671
01:35:54,070 --> 01:35:57,610
And as I was mentioning,
evaluation is a hard problem.

1672
01:35:57,610 --> 01:36:01,710
So you have all these
angles that you can explore.

1673
01:36:01,710 --> 01:36:05,590
And it's not one number
that's going to tell you

1674
01:36:05,590 --> 01:36:06,450
what you care about.

1675
01:36:06,450 --> 01:36:08,630
It's the combination
of all of these.

1676
01:36:08,630 --> 01:36:13,250
And in the end, it's tailored
to what you actually need.

1677
01:36:13,250 --> 01:36:17,230
So you would need to see
the strengths and weaknesses

1678
01:36:17,230 --> 01:36:21,310
of a given model and to
determine which one corresponds

1679
01:36:21,310 --> 01:36:24,590
to your use case.

1680
01:36:24,590 --> 01:36:29,010
So I'm going to come back to one
question about alignment here.

1681
01:36:29,010 --> 01:36:33,150
So we're going to see at the
next lecture a further step

1682
01:36:33,150 --> 01:36:35,590
into aligning the
model to do what

1683
01:36:35,590 --> 01:36:39,150
you want to do in a step
called preference tuning.

1684
01:36:39,150 --> 01:36:43,790
And then the combination of fine
tuning and preference tuning,

1685
01:36:43,790 --> 01:36:46,670
which comes after
pre-training, is what

1686
01:36:46,670 --> 01:36:48,630
we call alignment of the model.

1687
01:36:48,630 --> 01:36:52,090
So these two steps
are called alignments.

1688
01:36:52,090 --> 01:36:55,370
And I want to call
out one other thing.

1689
01:36:55,370 --> 01:36:57,850
There is one step we
didn't mention here

1690
01:36:57,850 --> 01:37:02,050
that is called mid training
that has been emerging

1691
01:37:02,050 --> 01:37:05,930
very recently, which
consists in a step

1692
01:37:05,930 --> 01:37:10,890
just after pre-training in
aligning the kind of data

1693
01:37:10,890 --> 01:37:13,930
that the model is being
trained on to the tasks

1694
01:37:13,930 --> 01:37:15,770
that you really care about.

1695
01:37:15,770 --> 01:37:18,130
So it's the same
pre-training objective

1696
01:37:18,130 --> 01:37:22,570
but aligning the kind of tasks
and the kind of data sets

1697
01:37:22,570 --> 01:37:24,570
to something that
you care about.

1698
01:37:24,570 --> 01:37:26,790
And yeah, so it's
an emerging trend.

1699
01:37:26,790 --> 01:37:28,930
I have not mentioned it,
but just so that you know,

1700
01:37:28,930 --> 01:37:31,620
mid training is
something that you

1701
01:37:31,620 --> 01:37:33,620
would have between
pre-training and fine tuning.

1702
01:37:36,120 --> 01:37:36,620
All good?

1703
01:37:39,390 --> 01:37:39,890
OK.

1704
01:37:39,890 --> 01:37:40,470
Great.

1705
01:37:40,470 --> 01:37:44,130
So now, we're going to tackle
one aspect of the challenges

1706
01:37:44,130 --> 01:37:46,630
that we had mentioned
regarding fine tuning, which

1707
01:37:46,630 --> 01:37:50,110
is computational expense--

1708
01:37:50,110 --> 01:37:52,750
the fact of being
computationally expensive.

1709
01:37:52,750 --> 01:37:56,950
And we're going to look at it
with one well-known technique

1710
01:37:56,950 --> 01:38:00,550
called LoRA, which
is a technique

1711
01:38:00,550 --> 01:38:05,150
to fine tune your weights
at the fine tuning stage

1712
01:38:05,150 --> 01:38:07,190
in an efficient manner.

1713
01:38:07,190 --> 01:38:08,970
So it's widely used.

1714
01:38:08,970 --> 01:38:12,490
And it saves a lot of compute.

1715
01:38:12,490 --> 01:38:15,950
So when you look at
your weight matrices,

1716
01:38:15,950 --> 01:38:20,190
instead of directly fine
tuning the whole weight matrix,

1717
01:38:20,190 --> 01:38:25,710
the LoRA technique
decomposes the fine tuning

1718
01:38:25,710 --> 01:38:30,910
between the weights of
the pre-trained model

1719
01:38:30,910 --> 01:38:35,870
and additional weights that
it decomposes into a low rank

1720
01:38:35,870 --> 01:38:37,830
multiplication.

1721
01:38:37,830 --> 01:38:43,370
So in this formulation,
the pre-trained weights

1722
01:38:43,370 --> 01:38:45,230
that you have is frozen.

1723
01:38:45,230 --> 01:38:47,370
So this W0 is frozen.

1724
01:38:47,370 --> 01:38:51,890
And then B and A are the
matrices that you need to tune.

1725
01:38:51,890 --> 01:38:54,610
So B and A are typically--

1726
01:38:54,610 --> 01:38:58,650
so they have dimensions that
will match the number of rows

1727
01:38:58,650 --> 01:39:01,210
and number of
columns respectively

1728
01:39:01,210 --> 01:39:04,490
for the number of rows of B
and number of columns of A.

1729
01:39:04,490 --> 01:39:09,370
But then the dimension of the
columns of B and then rows of A

1730
01:39:09,370 --> 01:39:13,810
is R, which is the rank of these
matrices, which is typically

1731
01:39:13,810 --> 01:39:16,530
taken very small.

1732
01:39:16,530 --> 01:39:22,010
So the dimensions of W is
typically hundreds or thousands,

1733
01:39:22,010 --> 01:39:29,130
and the dimension of R is
typically up to 10 or O of 10.

1734
01:39:29,130 --> 01:39:33,410
So as you can imagine, it
results in much less weights

1735
01:39:33,410 --> 01:39:33,920
to train.

1736
01:39:37,770 --> 01:39:40,130
And then I will mention
just other techniques

1737
01:39:40,130 --> 01:39:45,150
to improve efficiency and
then ease the fine tuning,

1738
01:39:45,150 --> 01:39:49,310
some methods called a
prefix tuning and adapters.

1739
01:39:49,310 --> 01:39:53,410
So they're explained
in the class textbook.

1740
01:39:53,410 --> 01:39:57,590
But we're not going to dive
deep into them because they're

1741
01:39:57,590 --> 01:39:58,850
less commonly used.

1742
01:39:58,850 --> 01:40:01,750
But just so that you know.

1743
01:40:01,750 --> 01:40:06,850
So let's walk through in
detail how does LoRA work.

1744
01:40:06,850 --> 01:40:10,530
So when you want to
fine tune your model,

1745
01:40:10,530 --> 01:40:12,110
so you have all
these ways for which

1746
01:40:12,110 --> 01:40:14,510
you have already
learned a distribution

1747
01:40:14,510 --> 01:40:15,950
at pre-training time.

1748
01:40:15,950 --> 01:40:19,630
So one naive way of
operating fine tuning

1749
01:40:19,630 --> 01:40:22,870
would be to directly
iterate on these weights.

1750
01:40:22,870 --> 01:40:24,810
But what we're doing
here, as we said,

1751
01:40:24,810 --> 01:40:28,310
is to decompose these into the
weights that we have already

1752
01:40:28,310 --> 01:40:32,470
pre-trained on and this
product of matrices.

1753
01:40:32,470 --> 01:40:37,590
And what LoRA says is that
you can do a forward pass

1754
01:40:37,590 --> 01:40:41,130
on both these
terms and then adds

1755
01:40:41,130 --> 01:40:43,930
these quantities in the end.

1756
01:40:43,930 --> 01:40:50,730
And A and B is going to
be a characterization

1757
01:40:50,730 --> 01:40:52,650
of your task of interest.

1758
01:40:52,650 --> 01:40:55,370
So let's say you
have a model that--

1759
01:40:55,370 --> 01:40:57,370
so Afshin was mentioning
the kinds of tasks

1760
01:40:57,370 --> 01:41:01,190
that you can maybe specialize
your model on, for example,

1761
01:41:01,190 --> 01:41:02,570
spam detection.

1762
01:41:02,570 --> 01:41:05,570
So you would take your
pre-trained model,

1763
01:41:05,570 --> 01:41:09,010
instantiate this B
and A in weights,

1764
01:41:09,010 --> 01:41:12,650
in the weights of your
model, fine tune on them.

1765
01:41:12,650 --> 01:41:16,010
And then what you will
have is that B and A

1766
01:41:16,010 --> 01:41:19,850
are going to be specific to
this task of spam detection,

1767
01:41:19,850 --> 01:41:23,810
similarly for sentiment
extraction and so on.

1768
01:41:23,810 --> 01:41:26,450
So it's a very nice
property that you

1769
01:41:26,450 --> 01:41:30,890
can start from a base model,
further tune your weights,

1770
01:41:30,890 --> 01:41:34,080
and then have your A's and
B's that are task specific.

1771
01:41:37,390 --> 01:41:42,870
So I want to comment
now on where were

1772
01:41:42,870 --> 01:41:46,750
these matrices being learned.

1773
01:41:46,750 --> 01:41:49,910
So in the original
paper of LoRA,

1774
01:41:49,910 --> 01:41:55,070
it mentioned training only
on the attention matrices.

1775
01:41:55,070 --> 01:41:58,910
But later on, people
realized that it might not

1776
01:41:58,910 --> 01:42:02,310
be the place where
it has the most

1777
01:42:02,310 --> 01:42:05,750
positive impact on performance.

1778
01:42:05,750 --> 01:42:10,390
And then there is a blog
that came out a few weeks ago

1779
01:42:10,390 --> 01:42:14,870
that studies this into
detail, and then they

1780
01:42:14,870 --> 01:42:18,830
realized that the feed-forward
blocks are actually

1781
01:42:18,830 --> 01:42:22,270
those where putting
LoRA is most beneficial.

1782
01:42:22,270 --> 01:42:28,550
So today, typically, both these
components carry LoRA matrices,

1783
01:42:28,550 --> 01:42:33,110
but the bulk of the
performance improvements

1784
01:42:33,110 --> 01:42:35,920
is actually contained in
the feed-forward block.

1785
01:42:38,730 --> 01:42:42,570
And then I want to mention
two interesting properties

1786
01:42:42,570 --> 01:42:44,810
about LoRA.

1787
01:42:44,810 --> 01:42:47,770
So when you fine tune
with LoRA weights,

1788
01:42:47,770 --> 01:42:50,470
you want to use a
higher learning rate.

1789
01:42:50,470 --> 01:42:55,210
So typically, 10 times
more is the guidance.

1790
01:42:55,210 --> 01:42:57,770
And then one interesting
fact is that it

1791
01:42:57,770 --> 01:43:03,810
doesn't perform as well when you
train it with larger batch size.

1792
01:43:03,810 --> 01:43:06,890
So I don't have a good
theoretical explanation

1793
01:43:06,890 --> 01:43:08,810
to give you for each of them.

1794
01:43:08,810 --> 01:43:12,610
It's more empirical observations
that have been emitted.

1795
01:43:12,610 --> 01:43:17,090
But to give the main lines
behind the mindset shared

1796
01:43:17,090 --> 01:43:20,210
from people who study
this phenomenon,

1797
01:43:20,210 --> 01:43:25,010
the first one might be guided
by the rank of the LoRA matrices

1798
01:43:25,010 --> 01:43:26,150
that might be small.

1799
01:43:26,150 --> 01:43:29,330
And as a result, given
the regions of space

1800
01:43:29,330 --> 01:43:32,930
that it needs to explore, you
need a higher learning rate.

1801
01:43:32,930 --> 01:43:35,430
And then the second
one, the hypothesis

1802
01:43:35,430 --> 01:43:45,030
here is that the training
dynamic of products of matrices

1803
01:43:45,030 --> 01:43:47,430
is different than a full matrix.

1804
01:43:47,430 --> 01:43:53,750
And this is where the increasing
batch size phenomenon occurs.

1805
01:43:53,750 --> 01:43:57,210
So it's basically
the explanations,

1806
01:43:57,210 --> 01:44:01,110
tentative explanations
given there.

1807
01:44:01,110 --> 01:44:07,590
So now, we're going to explore
an optimization of this.

1808
01:44:07,590 --> 01:44:10,830
But before I dive
deep into that part,

1809
01:44:10,830 --> 01:44:13,250
does anyone have any
questions on the LoRA part?

1810
01:44:13,250 --> 01:44:13,750
Yep.

1811
01:44:23,590 --> 01:44:24,090
Yep.

1812
01:44:24,090 --> 01:44:24,590
Great point.

1813
01:44:24,590 --> 01:44:28,550
So the question is, do you
do grid search on the rank?

1814
01:44:28,550 --> 01:44:29,510
So you could.

1815
01:44:29,510 --> 01:44:32,690
So it's a design choice
to rank R. Typically,

1816
01:44:32,690 --> 01:44:35,010
people would have
done it before you.

1817
01:44:35,010 --> 01:44:38,730
So you have an idea of what
rank could be well suited

1818
01:44:38,730 --> 01:44:41,330
for your use case.

1819
01:44:41,330 --> 01:44:43,190
So you could definitely
do grid search,

1820
01:44:43,190 --> 01:44:45,610
or you could just
pick a popular value.

1821
01:44:45,610 --> 01:44:48,310
I think a 4 is used commonly.

1822
01:44:48,310 --> 01:44:51,070
You can just go
with one of them.

1823
01:44:51,070 --> 01:44:51,570
Yeah.

1824
01:44:51,570 --> 01:44:54,530
And we are going to see
that the reduction in number

1825
01:44:54,530 --> 01:45:00,210
of parameters is so huge
already that reducing even more

1826
01:45:00,210 --> 01:45:02,010
maybe doesn't matter that much.

1827
01:45:02,010 --> 01:45:07,250
That initial reduction by orders
of magnitude goes a long way,

1828
01:45:07,250 --> 01:45:09,710
and that is just a
hyperparameter tuning.

1829
01:45:09,710 --> 01:45:12,170
And you can see a
given rank in a given

1830
01:45:12,170 --> 01:45:15,810
setup as being a design choice.

1831
01:45:15,810 --> 01:45:17,370
So we have two
minutes, and we're

1832
01:45:17,370 --> 01:45:22,210
going to quickly
cover quantized LoRA.

1833
01:45:22,210 --> 01:45:24,410
So the techniques
that Afshin mentioned

1834
01:45:24,410 --> 01:45:28,130
just now regarding
quantizing weights

1835
01:45:28,130 --> 01:45:33,710
and so reducing the
memory footprint

1836
01:45:33,710 --> 01:45:37,190
is something that we're
going to see just here.

1837
01:45:37,190 --> 01:45:41,550
So when you look at these
matrices W0 and A and B,

1838
01:45:41,550 --> 01:45:43,990
what people have
done in this paper

1839
01:45:43,990 --> 01:45:52,990
is to quantize the weights of W0
into a format that is very smart

1840
01:45:52,990 --> 01:45:55,910
and then compute and
iterate on these matrices

1841
01:45:55,910 --> 01:45:58,590
that are being learned, A and
B in full precision, which

1842
01:45:58,590 --> 01:45:59,836
is in that case BF16.

1843
01:46:02,870 --> 01:46:07,670
And then the quantization
of these frozen weights

1844
01:46:07,670 --> 01:46:09,030
is super smart.

1845
01:46:09,030 --> 01:46:12,430
It's in a format
called NF4, which

1846
01:46:12,430 --> 01:46:16,070
assumes that the weights
are distributed normally.

1847
01:46:16,070 --> 01:46:22,670
And it splits the space into
quantiles rather than buckets

1848
01:46:22,670 --> 01:46:26,510
of fixed size, which puts
about the same amount of number

1849
01:46:26,510 --> 01:46:28,350
of values into each.

1850
01:46:28,350 --> 01:46:33,130
So it optimizes the bits
that you use for encoding.

1851
01:46:33,130 --> 01:46:38,170
And what it does is that it does
a double quantization process.

1852
01:46:38,170 --> 01:46:40,490
So it quantizes the weights.

1853
01:46:40,490 --> 01:46:45,130
And then in a second
step, it quantizes

1854
01:46:45,130 --> 01:46:48,430
the quantization constants that
we didn't see at length here.

1855
01:46:48,430 --> 01:46:54,890
But basically, when you want
to convert your full weights in

1856
01:46:54,890 --> 01:46:57,330
and out of quantized
states, you have

1857
01:46:57,330 --> 01:46:59,670
constants that are generated.

1858
01:46:59,670 --> 01:47:03,610
And they propose to quantize
these constants as well.

1859
01:47:03,610 --> 01:47:11,030
So this method generated
minus 16X VRAM savings,

1860
01:47:11,030 --> 01:47:15,250
and then the double quantization
methods gave some extra savings

1861
01:47:15,250 --> 01:47:16,230
but not that much.

1862
01:47:16,230 --> 01:47:18,050
But it's interesting to know.

1863
01:47:18,050 --> 01:47:20,170
And then we are exactly on time.

1864
01:47:20,170 --> 01:47:22,360
Thank you for your time.